  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Chacune des figures ci-bas contient une esquisse d'une surface <m>\cS</m> et son bord <m>\partial \cS</m>. Le théorème de Stokes dit que
  <m>\oint_{\partial \cS} \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}   =\iint_{\cS} \vnabla \times \vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}</m> lorsque <m>\vn</m> est un vecteur unitaire normal à <m>\cS</m> compatible avec l'orientation du bord. Dans chaque cas, esquisser un vecteur normal unitaire convenable. </p>

  <sidebyside widths="5% 27% 5% 27% 5% 22%">
  <p>(a)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientA"/>
  <p>(b)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientB"/>
  <p>(c)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientC"/>
  </sidebyside>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Une approche est de faire d'abord une figure comme celle-ci
    </p>

  <sidebyside width="26%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientAh"/>
  </sidebyside>

    <p>
      Puis, imaginer que l'esquisse est déformée pour obtenir  <m>\cS</m> tels que spécifiés.
    </p>
 </hint>

  <answer>
    <sidebyside widths="5% 27% 5% 27% 5% 22%">
    <p>(a)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientAs"/>
    <p>(b)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientBs"/>
    <p>(c)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientCs"/>
    </sidebyside>
  </answer>

  <solution><p>
  One approach is to first consider
  </p>
  <sidebyside width="26%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientAh"/>
  </sidebyside>
  <p>
  The correct normal to this surface is sketched in
  </p>
  <sidebyside width="26%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientAhs"/>
  </sidebyside>
  <p>
  It is correct because
  <ul>
  <li>
      if you walk along <m>\partial \cS</m> in the direction of the arrow
      on <m>\partial \cS</m>,
  </li>
  <li>
       with the vector from your feet to your head  having direction <m>\vn</m>
  </li>
  <li>
      then <m>\cS</m> is on your left hand side.
  </li>
  </ul>
  Now pretend that the surface <m>\cS</m> is made of rubber and that <m>\vn</m> is glued to <m>\cS</m>. We can push on this <m>\cS</m> to deform it to the <m>\cS</m> of part (a) or to the <m>\cS</m>
  of part (b). This gives the solutions to parts (a) and (b).
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="5% 27% 5% 27%">
    <p>(a)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientAs"/>
    <p>(b)</p> <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientBs"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  To deal with part (c), we can first rotate the flat disk that we considered above to get
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="18%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientCh"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  We can push on this <m>\cS</m> to deform it to the <m>\cS</m> of part (c). This gives
  the solution to part (c).
  </p>

  <p>(c)</p>

  <sidebyside width="22%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesOrientCs"/>
  </sidebyside>

  </solution>
