  <exercise>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Soit
      <ul>
        <li>
          <m>\cR</m> une région bornée dans le plan <m>xy</m>;
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Le bord <m>\cC</m> de <m>\cR</m> est formé d'une seule courbe fermée, simple et lisse par morceaux
              <ul>
                <li>
                  qui est orienté de façon compatible avec l'orientation de <m>\cR</m>, c'est-à-dire de sorte que si l'on marche le long de <m>\cC</m> dans le sens donné, alors <m>\cR</m> est à gauche;
              </li>
              </ul>
            </p>

            <sidebyside width="27%">
              <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/greens1"/>
            </sidebyside>
          </li>
          <li>
           <m>F_1(x,y)</m> et <m>F_2(x,y)</m> ont des dérivées continues en chaque point de  <m>\cR</m>.
          </li>
      </ul>
      Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour montrer que
      <me>
      \oint_{C} \big[F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x} +F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}\big]
      =\iint{\cR}\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                      - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y},
      </me>
      c'est-à-dire pour montrer le théorème de Green.
      </p>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Considérez le champ de vecteurs <m>\vF(x,y,z) = F_1(x,y)\,\vi +F_2(x,y)\,\vj</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <!-- <answer><p>
  See the solution.
  </p></answer> -->

  <solution><p> Think of the <m>xy</m>-plane as being the plane <m>z=0</m> in <m>\R^3</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="37%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokesGreen"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
      We are going to apply Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) with <m>\cS</m> being the given region <m>\cR</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
  and with <m>\vF(x,y,z) = F_1(x,y)\,\vi +F_2(x,y)\,\vj</m>.
  Then
  <ul>
  <li>
  the unit normal vector to <m>\cS</m> specified in Stokes theorem is <m>\vk</m>
  (if you walk along <m>\partial S = C</m> in the direction of the arrow
      on <m>\cC</m> with the vector from your feet to your head  having direction <m>\vk</m>
      then <m>S=R</m> is on your left hand side) and
  </li>
  <li>
  <m>\dee{S}=\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m> and
  </li>
  <li> the curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <me>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    F_1(x,y) &amp; F_2(x,y) &amp; 0 \end{matrix}\right]
  =\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                  - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\,\vk
  </me>
  </li>
  </ul>
  So Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{C} \big[F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x} +F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}\big]
  &amp;=\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
    =\iint_{S}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint{\cR}\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                  - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Montrer que <m>\ \oint_\cC\phi\vnabla\psi\cdot \dee{\vr}=-\oint_\cC\psi\vnabla\phi\cdot \dee{\vr}\ </m> pour toute paire de fonctions <m>\phi</m> et <m>\psi</m> qui ont des dérivées de premier ordre continues et toute courbe <m>\cC</m> qui est le bord d'une surface orientable lisse par morceaux.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <hint>
      <p>
        Commencerz par vérifier l'identité  <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>
      </p>
    </hint>
<!-- 
    <answer>
      <p>
        See the solution.
      </p>
    </answer> -->

    <solution>
      <p>
      We are to show that <m>\oint_{\cC}[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>.
      Suppose that <m>C=\partial S</m>. Then, by Stokes' theorem
      <me>
      \oint_{\cC}[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}
      =\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
      </me>
      We will show below
      that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>.
      This will imply that <m>\oint_{\cC}[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}=\vZero</m>.
      One way to see that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m> is
      <md>
        <mrow>
        \vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]
        &amp;=\vnabla\times[\vnabla(\phi\psi)] &amp;
        &amp; (\text{by part (c) of Theorem }<xref ref="thm_gradIdentities"/>)
        </mrow><mrow>
        &amp;=\vZero&amp;
        &amp; (\text{by part (b) of Theorem }<xref ref="thm_degTwoIdentities"/>)
        </mrow>
      </md>
    Another way to see that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m> is
    <md>
      <mrow>  \vnabla\!\times\![\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi] &amp;
        = \vnabla \phi\!\times\!\vnabla\psi+\phi\vnabla\!\times\!(\vnabla\psi)  +\vnabla\psi\!\times\!\vnabla\phi+\psi\vnabla\!\times\!(\vnabla\phi)
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        &amp;=\vnabla\phi\times\vnabla\psi +\vnabla\psi\times\vnabla\phi
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        &amp;\hskip1in\text{since } \phi\vnabla\times(\vnabla\psi)=\psi\vnabla\times(\vnabla\phi)=\vZero
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        &amp;=\vZero
      </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

