  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Soit <m>\cC</m> la courbe intersection du cylindre  <m>x^2+y^2=1</m> avec la surface <m>z=y^2</m> orientée dans le sens contraire des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en haut. Soit <m>\vF=(x^2-y, \, y^2+x, \, 1)</m>. Calculer   <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>
        <ol marker="(a)">
        <li> par calcul direct;
        </li>
        <li> en utilisant le théorème de Stokes.
        </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Pour paramétrer la courbe <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>, <m>z = y^2</m>, commencez par paramétrer le cercle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>. C'est-à-dire, trouvez <m>x(t)</m> et <m>y(t)</m> obéissant à <m>x(t)^2 + y(t)^2 = 1</m>. Ensuite, définissez <m>z(t) = y(t)^2</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>

    <answer>
      <p>
        (a) <m>2\pi</m> </p><p>
        (b) <m>2\pi</m>
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        (a) Observe that <m>x(t)=\cos t</m> and <m>y(t)=\sin t</m> obey <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2=1</m>. Then <m>z(t)=y(t)^2=\sin ^2 t</m>.  So we may parametrize the curve by  <m>\vr(t)=(\cos t, \sin t, \sin^2 t)</m> with <m>0\leqslant t\leqslant 2\pi</m>.  Then
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \vr'(t)&amp;=(-\sin t\,,\, \cos t \,,\, 2\sin t\cos t)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)&amp;=\big(\cos^2t-\sin t\,,\,\sin^2t+\cos t\,,\,1\big)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\vr'(t)&amp;=-\sin t\cos^2 t+\sin^2 t+\sin^2t\cos t +\cos^2t+2\sin t\cos t
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            &amp;=1+\frac{1}{3}\diff{}{t}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t]+\sin(2t)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \left\{1+\frac{1}{3}\diff{}{t}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t]+\sin(2t)\right\}\,\dee{t}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            &amp;=\left[t+\frac{1}{3}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t] -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2t) \right]_0^{2\pi}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
          &amp;=2\pi
          </mrow>
          </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        (b) Let <m>\cS</m> be the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> with <m>f(x,y)=y^2</m> and <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 1</m>. Since <m>\cC</m> is oriented counter clockwise when   viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis, Stokes' theorem requires that we use the normal <m>\vn</m> to <m>\cS</m> with positive <m>z</m> component. Hence
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \vn\,dS&amp;=\Big[-\pdiff{f}{x}\,\vi -\pdiff{f}{y}\,\vj+\vk\Big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y} =\Big[-2y\,\vj+\vk\Big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
              \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
              \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
              \pdiff{}{z} \\
              x^2-y &amp; y^2+x &amp; 1 \end{matrix}\right]  =2\vk
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,dS&amp;=2\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} &amp;=\iint_{\cS}\vnabla \times \vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S} = 2\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>  &amp;=2\pi
            </mrow>
          </md>
      </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Évaluer   <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>, où <m>\vF=ye^x\,\vi+(x+e^x)\,\vj+z^2\,\vk</m> et  <m>\cC</m> est la courbe
          <me>  \vr(t)=(1+\cos t)\,\vi+(1+\sin t)\,\vj+(1-\sin t-\cos t)\,\vk, \qquad   0\leqslant t\leqslant 2\pi.
          </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Appliquez le théorème de Stokes.
        Notez que <m>\vr(t) = x(t)\,\vi + y(t)\,\vj + z(t)\,\vk</m>
        obéit à <m>x(t) + y(t) + z(t) = 3</m>, pour tout <m>t</m>, et que <m>x(t)\,\vi + y(t)\,\vj
        =(1+\cos t)\,\vi + (1+\sin t)\,\vj</m> parcourt le cercle de rayon 1 centré à <m>(1,1)</m> dans le sens antihoraire.
      </p>
    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        We apply Stokes' theorem. First,
        <me>
        \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                          \pdiff{}{x} &amp;  \pdiff{}{y} &amp; \pdiff{}{z} \\
                          ye^x &amp; x+e^x &amp; z^2
                        \end{matrix}\right]
        =\big(1+e^x-e^x\big)\,\vk
        =\vk
        </me>

        Note that <m>\vr(t) = x(t)\,\vi+y(t)\,\vj +z(t)\,\vk</m> obeys <m>x(t)+y(t)+z(t)=3</m>, for every <m>t</m>, and that <m>x(t)\,\vi+y(t)\,\vj         =(1+\cos t)\,\vi+(1+\sin t)\,\vj</m> runs counterclockwise around the circle of radius 1 centered on <m>(1,1)</m>. So we choose <m>\cS</m> to be the part of the plane <m>G(x,y,z)=x+y+z=3</m> with <m>(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1</m>. Then, by Stokes' Theorem,
        <me>
        \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
        =\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
        =\iint_{\cS} \vk\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
        </me>
        with
        <me>
        \vn\,\dee{S} = \pm \frac{\vnabla G}{\vnabla G\cdot\vk}\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
        = \pm\big(\vi+\vj+\vk\big)\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
        </me>
        As <m>(1+\cos t)\,\vi+(1+\sin t)\,\vj</m> runs counterclockwise around
        the circle <m>(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1</m>, Stokes' theorem
        specifies the plus sign and
        <me>
        \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
        =\iint_{(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1} \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
        =\pi
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Trouver la valeur de  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vnabla \times \vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}</m>, où  <m>\vF = \big( z - y, \, x, \, -x \big)</m> et <m>\cS</m> est l'hémisphère
        <me>
          \Set{(x, y, z) \in\R^3 }{ x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 4,\ z \geqslant 0}
        </me>
      orienté de sorte que le vecteur normal unitaire pointe en s'éloignant du centre de l'hémisphère.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint><p>
  La forme de l'intégrale devrait être une indication...
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>8\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The boundary of <m>\cS</m> is
  <me>
  \partial S = \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=0,\ x^2+y^2=4}
  </me>
  and can be parametrized
  <me>
  \vr(\theta) = 2\cos\theta\,\vi +2\sin\theta\,\vj\qquad
  0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi
  </me>
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="28%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE11A_4"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  So, by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>)
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^{2\pi} (\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\vi+2\cos\theta\,\vj-2\cos\theta\,\vk}^
                 {\vF(\vr(\theta))})\cdot
       (\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\vi+2\cos\theta\,\vj}^
                  {\vr'(\theta)})\ \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=4\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=8\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 1998D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Soit <m>\cS</m> la portion  de la surface <m>z=16-{(x^2+y^2)}^2</m> qui se trouve sur le plan <m>xy</m>. Soit  <m>\vF = x\ln(1+z) \, \vi + x(3+y) \, \vj + y\cos z \, \vk </m>.
        Calculer
          <me>
        \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S},
        </me>
        où  <m>\vn</m> est le  vecteur normal à  <m>\cS</m> pointant vers le haut.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <hint>
      <p>
      La forme de l'intégrale devrait être un indication en soi...
      </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>12\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        The boundary of <m>\cS</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>, <m>z=0</m>. Let <m>\cC</m> be this circle, oriented by the parametrization <m>x(t)=2\cos t</m>, <m>y(t)=2\sin t</m>, <m>z(t)=0</m>. By Stokes' theorem
          <md>
          <mrow>
          &amp;\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
          =\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
          =\int_0^{2\pi}\vF(2\cos t,2\sin t,0)\cdot \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\ \dee{t}
          </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[0\,\vi+2\cos t(3+2\sin t)\,\vj+2\sin t\,\vk\big]\cdot
          \big[-2\sin t\,\vi+2\cos t\vj\big]\ \dee{t}
          </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[12\cos^2 t+8\cos^2t\sin t\big]\ \dee{t}
          </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[6+6\cos(2t)+8\cos^2t\sin t\big]\ \dee{t}
          </mrow><mrow>
          &amp;\hskip0.25in=\Big[6t+3\sin(2t) -\frac{8}{3}\cos^3 t\Big]_0^{2\pi}
          =12\pi
          </mrow>
          </md>
        For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t\,\dee{t}</m>, see Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    </p>
    </solution>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <m>\cS</m> be the surface specified in the question, with upward pointing normal, and
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\cD</m> be the disk <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 4,\ z=0}</m>, with normal <m>\vn=\vk</m>, and
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\cC</m> be the circle <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2=4,\ z=0}</m>, oriented as in the figure below.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <sidebyside width="27%">
      <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE98D_6"/>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        Note that <m>\cC</m> is the boundary curve for both <m>\cS</m> and <m>\cD</m>. So, by Stokes' theorem, twice
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S} &amp;=\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}  =\iint_{\cD}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
          </mrow>
          <mrow> &amp;=\iint_{\cD}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vk\,\dee{S}
          </mrow>
        </md>
        Now the <m>\vk</m> component of <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vk
            &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big[x(3+y)\big]
            - \pdiff{}{y}\big[x\ln(1+z)\big]
            =3+y
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

    <p>As <m>y</m> is odd under <m>y\rightarrow-y</m> and <m>\cD</m> is invariant under <m>y\rightarrow-y</m>, we have <m>\iint_{\cD}y\,\dee{S}=0</m>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
    = \iint_{\cD}(3+y)\,\dee{S}
    =3\iint_{\cD}\dee{S}
    =3\,\text{Area}(\cS) =3\,\pi 2^2=12\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\cC</m> l'intersection du paraboloïde  <m>z=4-x^2-y^2</m> et du cylindre <m>x^2+(y-1)^2=1</m>, orientée dans le sens contraire des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en haut. Soit <m>\vF=xz\,\vi+x\,\vj+yz\,\vk</m>. Trouver     <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint><p>
  Quel est le titre de cette section?
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Let <m>\cS</m> be the portion of the paraboloid <m>z=f(x,y)=4-x^2-y^2</m>
  with <m>x^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1</m> and let <m>\vn</m> be the upward normal to <m>\cS</m>.
  For this surface
  <me>
  \vn\,\dee{S}=\big(-f_x(x,y)\,\vi -f_y(x,y)\,\vj +\vk\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
     = \big(2x\,\vi+2y\,\vj+\vk\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </me>
  by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>). As <m>(x,y,z)</m> runs over
  <m>\cS</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over the circular disk
  <me>
  D = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1}
  </me>
  For the given vector field
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  xz &amp; x &amp; yz
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=z\,\vi+x\,\vj+\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  so that, by Stokes' theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_D
     \big[2x\overbrace{(4-x^2-y^2)}^{z=f(x,y)}+2xy+1\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  By oddness under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m>, all terms integrate to zero except
  for the last. So
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\iint_D\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  =\text{Area}(D)
  =\pi
  </me>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\vF = - ye^z\,\vi + x^3\cos z\,\vj + z\sin(xy)\,\vk</m> et
  <m>\cS</m> la portion de la surface <m> z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)</m> qui se trouve au-dessus du carré <m>-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1</m>, <m>-1\leqslant y\leqslant 1</m> du plan <m>xy</m>. Trouver le flux de  <m>\vnabla\times \vF</m> vers le haut à travers <m>\cS</m>.
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Nous devons évaluer une intégrale de flux de la forme <m>\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m>. Cela ressemble bien à un côté du théorème de Stokes.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <answer><p>
  <m>8</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The surface
  <md>
  <mrow>
  S&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ -1\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ z\geqslant 0,\ z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)}
  </mrow><mrow>
   &amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ -1\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ \ z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Note that when <m>x=1</m> or <m>x=-1</m> or <m>y=1</m> or <m>y=-1</m>,
  we have <m>z= (1-x^2)(1-y^2)=0</m>.  So the boundary of <m>\cS</m>,  call it <m>\cC</m>,
  is the boundary of the square <m>-1\leqslant x,y\leqslant 1</m>, <m>z=0</m>, oriented
  counterclockwise. Here is a sketch of <m>\cC</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="36%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/singGnA"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  Apply Stokes' theorem. Observing that <m>z=0</m> on <m>\cC</m>
  so that <m>\vF = -y\,\vi +x^3\,\vj</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\oint_{\cC}[-y\,\vi+x^3\vj]\cdot \dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\underbrace{\int_{-1}^1 -(-1)\,\dee{x}}_{y=-1{\rm\ side}}
     +\underbrace{\int_{-1}^1 (1)^3\,\dee{y}}_{x=1{\rm\ side}}
     + \underbrace{\int^{-1}_1 -(1)\,\dee{x}}_{y=1{\rm\ side}}
     + \underbrace{\int^{-1}_1 (-1)^3\,\dee{y}}_{x=-1{\rm\ side}}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=8
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Calculer l'intégrale  <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>, avec <m>\vF = (e^{x^2} - yz, \, \sin y - yz, \, xz + 2y)</m> et <m>\cC</m> le parcours triangulaire de <m>(1, 0, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 1, 0)</m> puis à  <m>(0, 0, 1)</m> et qui retourne à <m>(1, 0, 0)</m>.
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Le champ vectoriel <m>\vF</m> semble trop compliqué pour une évaluation directe de l'intégrale de ligne. Essayez donc le théorème de Stokes.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>1</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  We shall apply Stokes' Theorem. The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    e^{x^2} - yz &amp; \sin y - yz &amp; xz + 2y\end{matrix}\right|
  </mrow><mrow>&amp;=(2+y)\,\vi-(z+y)\,\vj+(0+z)\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The curve <m>\cC</m> is a triangle. All three vertices of the triangle obey
  <m>x+y+z=1</m>. So the triangle is the boundary
  of the surface <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x\geqslant 0,\ y\geqslant 0,\ z=1-x-y\geqslant 0}</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="23%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/domainTriangleA"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  The equation of the surface is <m>z=f(x,y)=1-x-y</m>.
  So, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\ \dee{S}
  &amp;=\big(-f_x\,\vi-f_y\,\vj+\vk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Here <m>\vn</m> is the upward pointing unit normal.
  The set of points <m>(x,y)</m> for which there is a corresponding <m>(x,y,z)</m>
  in <m>\cS</m> is  <m>T=\Set{(x,y)}{x\geqslant 0,\ y\geqslant 0,\ x+y\leqslant 1}</m>, which is a triangle
  of area <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
  Since
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;=[(2+y)\vi-(z+y)\vj+(0+z)\vk]\cdot(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 2\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  we have
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}&amp;=\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_T 2\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  = 2\,\text{Area}(T)
  =1
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\vF(x,y,z)=-z\,\vi+x\,\vj+y\,\vk</m> un champ de vecteurs. Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour calculer
  <m>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr},
  </m>
  où <m>\cC</m> est l'intersection du plan <m>z=y</m> et de l'ellipsoïde
  <m>\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{2}+\frac{z^2}{2}=1</m>, orientée dans le sens contraire des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en-haut.
  </p>

  </statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>4\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Stokes' theorem, which is Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>, says that <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\iint_{\cS}\nabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m> for any surface <m>\cS</m> whose boundary is
  <m>\cC</m>. For the given vector field
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \nabla\times\vF(x,y,z)
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  -z &amp; x &amp; y
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\vi-\vj+\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Choose
  <md>
  <mrow>
  S &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=y,\ \tfrac{x^2}{4}+\tfrac{y^2}{2}+\tfrac{z^2}{2}\leqslant 1}
  </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=y,\ \tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\leqslant 1}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  to be the part of the plane <m>z=y</m> bounded by the ellipsoid.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="71%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE01DQ4"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  As <m>\cS</m> is part of the plane <m>z=f(x,y)=y</m>, (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>), gives that
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S} &amp;=\pm \big(-f_x\,,\,-f_y\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\pm (0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  As <m>\cC</m> has the standard orientation (counter-clockwise when viewed
  from high on the <m>z</m>-axis), we want <m>\vn</m> to have a positive <m>z</m>-component.
  So
  <m>\vn\,\dee{S}= (0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y} </m>.
  From the second form of <m>\cS</m> given above, we see that as <m>(x,y,z)</m>
  runs over <m>\cS</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over
  <me>
  D=\Set{(x,y)}{\tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\leqslant 1}
  </me>
  Consequently, Stokes' theorem gives that
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}

  &amp;=\iint_D\overbrace{(1,-1,1)}^{\nabla\times\vF}\cdot
              \overbrace{(0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y} }^{\vn\,\dee{S}}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=2\int{\cD}\dee{x}\dee{y}
  =2\,\text{Area}(D)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The ellipse <m>\cD</m>, that is <m>\tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\leqslant 1</m>, has semi-axes
  <m>a=2</m> and <m>b=1</m> and hence area <m>\pi ab=2\pi</m>. Finally
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =2\,\text{Area}(D)
  =4\pi
  </me>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Considérer le champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF(x,y, z) = z^2 \,\vi + x^2 \,\vj + y^2\,\vk</m> dans <m>\R^3</m>.
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Calculer l'intégrale de ligne  <m>I_1 = \int_{C_1}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> lorsque  <m>C_1</m> est la courbe formée par les segments de droites
  <m>L_1</m> de <m>(2, 0, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>,
  <m>L_2</m> de <m>(0, 2, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 0, 2)</m> et finalement
  <m>L_3</m> de <m>(0, 0, 2)</m> à <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Une courbe fermée simple  <m>C_2</m> sur plan <m>E\,:\, x + y + z = 2</m>, qui délimite une région <m>\cR</m> de ce plan dont l'aire est <m>3</m> et est orientée dans le sens contraire aux aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue de la direction du demi-axe  <m>x</m> positif. Calculer l'intégrale  <m>I_2 = \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>8</m></p><p>
  (b) <m>4\sqrt{3}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Note that the curve of part (a) is a simple closed curve that lies in the plane <m>x+y+z=2</m> and is oriented in a counterclockwise direction as observed from the positive <m>x</m>-axis. The curve of part (a) encloses a triangle.
    </p>

  <sidebyside width="40%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE16D_9"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  Two of the sides of the triangle
  are <m>(0,2,0)-(2,0,0)=(-2,2,0)</m> and  <m>(0,0,2)-(0,2,0)=(0,-2,2)</m> so the
  area of the triangle is
  <me>
  \frac{1}{2}\big|(-2,2,0)\times (0,-2,2)\big|
  =\frac{1}{2} \det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi&amp;\vj&amp;\vk\\
       -2&amp; 2&amp; 0 \\  0 &amp; -2 &amp; 2 \end{matrix}\right]
  =\frac{1}{2}\big|(4,4,4)\big|
  =2\sqrt{3}
  </me>
  So let's do part (b) first.
  </p>

  <p>(b) We are not told explicitly what <m>C_2</m> is, so we certainly can't
  do a direct evaluation. Instead, let's use Stokes' theorem
  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>). The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  z^2 &amp; x^2 &amp; y^2
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 2y\,\vi
      +2z\,\vj
      +2x\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The upward pointing unit normal to <m>E</m> is <m>\vn=\frac{\vi+\vj+\vk}{\sqrt{3}}</m>.
  So, by Stokes' theorem,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  I_2 &amp;= \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
      =\iint_R \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;    =\iint_R \big(2y\,\vi +2z\,\vj +2x\,\vk\big)\cdot
                 \frac{\vi+\vj+\vk}{\sqrt{3}}\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\iint_R \big(\overbrace{y + z + x}^
                               {=2\ {\rm on}\ R}\big)\,\dee{S}

  =\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\text{Area}(R)
  =4\sqrt{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p>(a) Denote by <m>T</m> the triangle enclosed by <m>C_1</m>. By the
  computation that we have just done in part (b)
  <md>
  <mrow>
  I_1 &amp;= \int_{C_1}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
       =\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\text{Area}(T)
       =8
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC = \cC_1 + \cC_2 + \cC_3</m> la courbe donnée par l'union des courbes paramétrées
  <md alignment="alignat">
  <mrow>
  \vr_1(t) &amp;= \big(2\cos t, 2\sin t, 0\big), &amp;\qquad
  &amp;0 \leqslant t \leqslant \pi/2,
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vr_2(t) &amp;= \big(0, 2\cos t, 2\sin t\big), &amp;
  &amp;0 \leqslant t \leqslant \pi/2,
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vr_3(t) &amp;= \big(2\sin t, 0, 2\cos t\big), &amp;
  &amp;0 \leqslant t \leqslant \pi/2.
  </mrow>
  </md>
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    Faire une esquisse de <m>\cC</m> montrant chacune des portions <m>\cC_1</m>, <m>\cC_2</m>, et <m>\cC_3</m> en indiquant les orientations induites par les paramétrages donnés.
  </li>
  <li>
    Trouver et paramétrer une surface orientée <m>\cS</m> dont le bord est <m>\cC</m> (avec les orientations données).
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer l'intégrale  <m>\int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>, où
  <me>
  \vF = \Big(y + \sin(x^2), \, z - 3x + \ln(1 + y^2), \, y + e^{z^2}\Big).
  </me>
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <answer>
  <p>(a)</p>
  <sidebyside width="40%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17A_5"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  (b) <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2=4,\ x\geqslant 0,\ y\geqslant 0,\ z\geqslant 0}</m>
  avec
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
  = 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
  + 2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
  + 2\cos\varphi\ \vk,
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;0\le\theta\le\frac{\pi}{2},\
  0\le\varphi\le\frac{\pi}{2}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  et
  <me>
  \vn = \cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
              +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
              +\cos\varphi\ \vk
  =\frac{1}{2}\,\vr(\theta,\varphi)
  </me>
  </p>

  <p>(c) <m>-4\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  (a) Observe that
  <ul>
  <li>
  the curve <m>C_1</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>xy</m>-plane,
  centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(2,0,0)</m> and
  ending at <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  the curve <m>C_2</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>yz</m>-plane,
  centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
  ending at <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  the curve <m>C_3</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>xz</m>-plane,
  centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
  ending at <m>(2,0,0)</m>.
  </li>
  </ul>
  Here is a sketch.
  </p>
  <sidebyside width="40%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17A_5"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  (b) <m>\cC</m> lies completely on the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m>. So it is natural to choose
  <me>
  S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2=4,\ x\geqslant 0,\ y\geqslant 0,\ z\geqslant 0}
  </me>
  and to parametrize <m>\cS</m> using spherical coordinates
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
  = 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
  + 2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
  + 2\cos\varphi\ \vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;0\le\theta\le\frac{\pi}{2},\
  0\le\varphi\le\frac{\pi}{2}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Since
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}
  &amp;= -2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\,\vi +2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\,\vj
  </mrow><mrow>
  \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}
  &amp;= 2\cos\theta\cos\varphi\,\vi +2\sin\theta\cos\varphi\,\vj
    - 2\sin\varphi\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  so that
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}\times\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}
  &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix} \vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
  -2\sin\theta\sin\varphi &amp; 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi &amp; 0 \\
  2\cos\theta\cos\varphi &amp; 2\sin\theta\cos\varphi &amp; - 2\sin\varphi
           \end{matrix}\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -4\cos\theta\sin^2\varphi\ \vi
     -4\sin\theta\sin^2\varphi\ \vj
     -4\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\ \vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}\times
              \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}\,\dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \mp 4\big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
              +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
              +\cos\varphi\ \vk\big)
            \sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  We want <m>\vn</m> to point outward, for compatibility with the orientation
  of <m>\cC</m>. So we choose the <m>+</m> sign.
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= 4\big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
              +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
              +\cos\varphi\ \vk\big)
            \sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=2\,\vr(\theta,\varphi)\sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p>(c) The vector field <m>\vF</m> looks too complicated for a direct evaluation
  of the line integral. So, in preparation for an application of Stokes'
  theorem, we compute
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi&amp;\vj&amp;\vk\\
       \frac{\partial }{\partial x}&amp;
          \frac{\partial }{\partial y}&amp;
          \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\\
   y + \sin(x^2) &amp; z - 3x + \ln(1 + y^2) &amp; y + e^{z^2}\end{matrix}\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -4\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So, by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.1in= \int_0^{\pi/2}\hskip-5pt\dee{\varphi}
                           \int_0^{\pi/2}\hskip-5pt\dee{\theta}\
  \big(-4\vk\big)\cdot
  \big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \vi
              +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \vj
              +\cos\varphi\ \vk\big)\
            4\sin\varphi
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.1in=-16 \int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\varphi}\int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\theta}\
                \cos\varphi\sin\varphi
  =16\ \frac{\pi}{2}\ \frac{\cos^2\varphi}{2}\bigg|_0^{\pi/2}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.1in=-4\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  On considère le cône <m>z = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m>. Noter que son sommet se trouve à l'origine  <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>. Le cône est orienté de sorte que, en chaque point, le vecteur normal pointe vers le bas (et en s'éloignant de l'axe des <m>z</m>). Dans les questions qui suivent, tant <m>\cS_1</m> que <m>\cS_2</m> sont orientées de la sorte.
  </p>

  <p>Soit <m>\vF = \big(-zy, \, zx, \, xy \cos(yz)\big)</m>.
  </p>

  <p><ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Soit <m>\cS_1</m> la portion du cône qui se trouve entre les plans
  <m>z = 0</m> et <m>z = 4</m>. Noter que <m>\cS_1</m> n'inclut aucune portion du plan  <m>z = 4</m>. Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour calculer la valeur de
  <me>
  \iint_{S_1} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}.
  </me>
  Faire une esquisse inscrivant les orientations de  <m>\cS_1</m> ainsi que du ou des contours d'intégration.
  </li>
  <li>
  Soit <m>\cS_2</m> la portion du cône qui se trouve au-dessous du plan <m>z = 4</m> et au-dessus du plan <m>z = 1</m>. Noter que <m>\cS_2</m> n'inclut aucune région des plans <m>z = 1</m> ou <m>z = 4</m>. Déterminer le flux de <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> à travers <m>\cS_2</m>. Justifier en incluant une esquisse de <m>\cS_2</m> qui inclut son orientation ainsi que celle des contours d'intégration.
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>-128\pi</m></p><p>
  (b) <m>-126\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
   (a)
  The boundary, <m>\partial S_1</m>, of <m>\cS_1</m> as specified in Stokes' theorem (Theorem
  <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) is the circle
  <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=4</m>, <m>z=4</m> oriented <em>clockwise</em> when viewed from high on
  the <m>z</m>-axis. That is, we can parametrize <m>\partial S_1</m> by
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vr(t) = 4\cos t\,\vi -4\sin t\,\vj +4\,\vk,\qquad 0\leqslant t\leqslant 2\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;= \big(16\sin t \,,\, 16\cos t \,,\, -16\sin t\cos t \cos(-16\sin t)  \big)
  </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
        \cdot
     \big(-4\sin t \,,\, -4\cos t \,,\, 0\big)\,\dee{t}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -64\,\dee{t}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and, by Stokes' theorem,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{S_1} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \oint_{\partial S_1} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
  = -64 \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{t}
  =-128\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="26% 29%" valign="middle">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/conePa"/>
   <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/conePb"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
   (b) The boundary, <m>\partial S_2</m>, of <m>\cS_2</m> consists of two parts,
  a circle in the plane <m>z=4</m> and a circle in the plane <m>z=1</m>.
  We'll call the first part <m>\partial S_{2a}</m>. It is the same as
  <m>\partial S_1</m>. We'll call the second part <m>\partial S_{2b}</m>.
  It is the circle <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=1</m>, <m>z=1</m> oriented <em>counterclockwise</em>
  when viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis.
  We can parametrize it
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vr(t) = \cos t\,\vi +\sin t\,\vj + \vk,\qquad 0\leqslant t\leqslant 2\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So, on <m>\partial S_{2b}</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;= \big(-\sin t \,,\, \cos t \,,\, \sin t\cos t \cos(\sin t)  \big)
        \cdot
     \big(-\sin t \,,\, \cos t \,,\, 0\big)\,\dee{t}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \dee{t}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and, by Stokes' theorem,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{S_2} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \oint_{\partial S_{2a}} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
     +\oint_{\partial S_{2b}} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -128\pi +  \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{t}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-126\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2015A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> la courbe d'intersection du plan <m>z = x + 4</m> et du cylindre <m>x^2 + y^2 = 4</m>, parcourue dans <em>le sens des aiguilles d'une montre</em> lorsque vue d'au-dessus.
  </p>

  <p>Soit  <m>\vF(x, y, z) = \big(x^3 + 2y, \, \sin(y) + z, \, x + \sin(z^2)\big)</m>.
  </p>

  <p>Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour évaluer l'intégrale de ligne
  <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>4\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Denote by
  <me>
  S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=x+4,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 4}
  </me>
  the part of the plane <m>z=x+4</m> that is contained in the cylinder
  <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>. Orient <m>\cS</m> by the downward pointing normal
  <m>\vn =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,0,-1)</m>. Then <m>\cC</m> is the boundary of <m>\cS</m>.
  The part of <m>\cC</m> and <m>\cS</m> that are in the first octant are sketched below.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="45%">
   <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE15A_5"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  We may parametrize <m>\cS</m> by
  <me>
  \vr(x,y) = (x,y, x+4)\qquad\text{with}\quad x^2+y^2\leqslant 4
  </me>
  So,
  <me>
  \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}
  = \det\left[\begin{matrix} \vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
  1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
  0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \end{matrix}\right]
  = \big(-1, 0, 1\big)
  </me>
  and, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S} = -\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times
              \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  = (1,0,-1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  We have chosen to <q><m>-</m></q> sign in <m>\vn\,\dee{S} =
         \pm\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times
          \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}</m>
  to give the downward pointing normal. As the curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  x^3 + 2y &amp; \sin(y) + z &amp;  x + \sin(z^2)
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -\vi -\vj -2\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\iint_{\cS} (-1,-1,-2)\cdot(1,0,-1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \dee{x}\dee{y}
  =4\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

