  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2009A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Calculer l'intégrale
  <me>
  \int_{\cC}\left(z+\frac{1}{1+z}\right)\dee{x}
           +xz\,\dee{y}
           +\left(3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}\right)\dee{z},
  </me>
  où <m>\cC</m> est la courbe paramétrée par
  <me>
  \vr(t) = \big( \cos t, \, \sin t, \, 1 - \cos^2 t \sin t \big), \qquad
  0 \leqslant t \leqslant 2\pi.
  </me>
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      La courbe <m>\cC</m> est la frontière d'une surface. Pour deviner la surface, exprimez la composante <m>z</m> de <m>\vr(t)</m> en termes des composantes <m>x</m> et <m>y</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>5\pi/4</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
   Let's try Stokes' theorem with
  <me>
  \vF = \left(z+\frac{1}{1+z}\right)\vi
           +xz\,\vj
           +\left(3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}\right)\vk
  </me>
  The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  z+\frac{1}{1+z} &amp; xz &amp; 3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=(3x-x)\vi
    -\left(3y-\frac{1}{(z+1)^2}-1+\frac{1}{(1+z)^2}\right)\vj +z\,\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=2x\,\vi +(1-3y)\,\vj+z\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Write
  <me>
  S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=f(x,y)=1-x^2y,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
  </me>
  For <m>\cS</m>, with the upward pointing normal, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S} &amp;=\big(-f_x\,,\,-f_y\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\big(2xy\,,\,x^2\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  so that
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;=\big\{4x^2y + (x^2-3x^2y) +\overbrace{(1-x^2y)}^{z}\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and, by Stokes' theorem,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    \big\{4x^2y + x^2-3x^2y + 1-x^2y\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    \big\{x^2+ 1\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  =\pi + \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  To evaluate the final remaining integral, let's switch to polar coordinates.
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\  \big(r\cos\theta)^2
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^1 \dee{r}\ r^3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \cos^2\theta
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Since <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
  =\left[\frac{\theta}{2}+\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
  =\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  we finally have
  <m>\int_0^1 \dee{r}\ r^3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \cos^2\theta=\frac{\pi}{4}</m>
  and
  <me>
  \int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =\pi+\frac{\pi}{4}
  =\frac{5\pi}{4}
  </me>
  For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
  <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>,
  see Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2008D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Une courbe fermée, simple et lisse par morceaux <m>\cC</m> se trouve sur le plan  <m>x + y + z = 1</m>. La région du plan que la courbe  <m>\cC</m> délimite a une aire égale à  <m>5</m>. La courbe <m>\cC</m> est orientée dans le sens des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue du demi-axe positif des <m>z</m>.
  </p>

  <p>Calculer la circulation de <m>\vF (x, y, z) = (z^2, \, x^2, \, y^2)</m> autour de  <m>\cC</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  Le fait que la surface ne soit pas complètement spécifiée devrait être un indice...
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-\frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  We are to evaluate a line integral around a curve <m>\cC</m>. We are told that
  <m>\cC</m> is the boundary of a surface <m>\cS</m> that is contained in the plane
  <m>x+y+z=1</m>, but we are not told precisely what <m>\cC</m> is. So we are going to have to use Stokes' theorem. The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
  z^2 &amp; x^2 &amp; y^2
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  = 2y\,\vi + 2z\,\vj +2x\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>) with
  <m>G(x,y,z)=x+y+z</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \dee{S} &amp;= \left|\frac{\vnabla\vG}{\vnabla\vG\cdot\vk}\right|\dee{x}\dee{y}
          =\sqrt{3}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\vnabla\vG}{\vnabla\vG\cdot\vk}\dee{x}\dee{y}
  = \pm \big(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  = \pm \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \big(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Because <m>\cC</m> is oriented in a clockwise direction as
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="43%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/stokes8"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  observed from the positive <m>z</m>-axis looking down at the plane,
  <m>\vn</m> is to point downwards, so that
  <me>
  \vn\,\dee{S} = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \big(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </me>
  On <m>\cS</m> we have <m>x+y+z=1</m>, so that Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} (\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} 2(y\,\vi+z\,\vj+x\,\vk)\cdot
          \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right) \big(\vi+\vj+\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\iint_{\cS} (y+z+x)\,\dee{S}
  =-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\iint_{\cS} \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  since <m>\cS</m> has area <m>5</m>.
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2008A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Soit  <m>\cC</m> la courbe fermée formée par les segments de droites allant de <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 1, 1)</m>, de <m>(0, 1, 1)</m> à <m>(0, 1, 2)</m>, de <m>(0, 1, 2)</m> à <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>, de  <m>(0, 2, 0)</m> à <m>(2, 2, 0)</m> et de  <m>(2, 2, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>.
  Soit
  <me>
  \vF = (-y+e^x\sin x)\,\vi
           +y^4\,\vj
           +\sqrt{z}\tan z\,\vk.
  </me>
  Calculer l'intégrale  <m>\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Nous devons évaluer l'intégrale de ligne d'un champ vectoriel compliqué autour d'une courbe fermée relativement compliquée. (Faites-en un croquis !) Cela suggère certainement que nous ne devrions pas essayer d'évaluer l'intégrale directement.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-2</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
  around a relatively complicated closed curve.
  That certainly suggests that
  we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. To see if
  Stokes' theorem looks promising, let's compute the curl
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
  -y+e^x\sin x &amp; y^4 &amp; \sqrt{z}\tan z
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  That's suggestive. Next we need to find a surface whose boundary is <m>\cC</m>.
  First, here is a sketch of <m>\cC</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="51%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE08A_8"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  We can choose the surface <m>\cS</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
  <ul>
  <li>
  the quadralateral <m>Q</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(0,1,1)</m>, <m>(0,1,2)</m> and <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  the triangle <m>T</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(0,2,0)</m> and <m>(2,2,0)</m>.
  </li>
  </ul>
  The normal to <m>Q</m> is <m>-\vi</m> and the normal to <m>T</m> is <m>-\vk</m>. Then Stokes'
  theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_Q  \vk\cdot(-\vi)\,\dee{S} + \iint_T  \vk\cdot(-\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= - \iint_T \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\text{Area}(T)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -\half\overbrace{2}^{\text{base}}\overbrace{2}^{\text{height}}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-2
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> l'intersection du cylindre   <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m> avec la surface <m>z = xy^2</m>, parcourue dans le sens des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en haut. Calculer
  <me>
  \int_{\cC}  (z + \sin z) \,\dee{x}
        + (x^3 - x^2 y) \,\dee{y}
        + (x \cos z - y) \,\dee{z}.
  </me>
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      L'intégrale semble compliquée. Calculez le rotationnel de <m>\vF</m> pour aider à évaluer si le théorème de Stokes serait plus facile.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The integral looks messy. Let's compute the curl of
  <me>
  \vF = (z + \sin z) \,\vi
        + (x^3 - x^2 y) \,\vj
        + (x \cos z - y) \,\vk
  </me>
  to help gauge if Stokes' theorem would be easier.
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  z + \sin z &amp; x^3 - x^2 y &amp; x \cos z - y
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\vi +\vj +(3x^2-2xy)\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  That's a lot simpler than <m>\vF</m>.
  For the surface <m>z=f(x,y)=xy^2</m>, with downward pointing normal (since <m>\cC</m> is traversed clockwise)
  <me>
  \vn\,\dee{S} = -\big(-f_x,-f_y,1\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  =\big(y^2,2xy,-1\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </me>
  by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
  So, writing
  <md>
  <mrow>
     S&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=xy^2,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
  </mrow><mrow>
     D&amp;=\Set{(x,y)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Stoke's theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\iint_D\big\{-y^2+2xy -3x^2+2xy\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\big\{3x^2+y^2-4xy\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  To evaluate this integral, switch to polar coordinates.
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=-\int_0^1\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\
             \big\{3r^2\cos^2\theta+r^2\sin^2\theta
                -4r^2\sin\theta\cos\theta\big\}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-4\pi \int_0^1\dee{r}\ r^3 =-\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  since
  <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin\theta\cos\theta\,\dee{\theta}
   =\frac{1}{2}\int_0^{2\pi}\sin(2\theta)\,\dee{\theta}=0</m>
  and
  <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
          =\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
          =\pi</m>.
  (See Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.)
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2006A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Calculer <m>\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m>, où <m>\cS</m> est la portion de la sphère <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m> au-dessus du plan  <m>z=1</m>, <m>\vn</m> pointe vers le haut et
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vF(x,y,z) = -y^2\,\vi  +x^3\,\vj + \big(e^x + e^y +z\big)\,\vk.
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  </statement>

  <hint><p>
  La forme de l'intégrande est un indice...
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>\frac{3\pi}{4}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Here is a sketch of the part of <m>\cS</m> in the first octant.
  </p>


  <sidebyside width="46%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE06A_6"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  The boundary, <m>\partial \cS</m>, of <m>\cS</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=1</m>, oriented counterclockwise when viewed from above.
  It is parametrized by
  <me>
  \vr(\theta) = \cos\theta\,\vi + \sin\theta\,\vj + \vk
  \qquad 0\leqslant \theta\leqslant 2\pi
  </me>
  So Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
    = \oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.5in = \int_0^{2\pi} \Big(\overbrace{
          -\sin^2\theta\,\vi +\cos^3\theta\,\vj+(\text{mess})\vk
                 }^{\vF(\vr(t))}\Big)\cdot
     \big(\overbrace{-\sin\theta\,\vi+\cos\theta\,\vj}^{\vr'(t)}\big)\
       \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big(\sin^3\theta +\cos^4\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The integral of any odd power of <m>\sin\theta</m> or <m>\cos\theta</m>
  over <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m> is zero.
  (See Example <xref ref="eg_stokesD"/>.)
  In particular, <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^3\theta\,\dee{\theta} =0</m>.
  To integrate <m>\cos^4\theta</m> we use the trig identity
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \cos^2\theta &amp;= \frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}
  </mrow><mrow>
  \implies
  \cos^4\theta &amp;= \frac{\cos^2(2\theta)+2\cos(2\theta) + 1}{4}
  </mrow><mrow>
               &amp;= \frac{1}{4}\ \frac{\cos(4\theta)+1}{2}
                  +\frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2} +\frac{1}{4}
  </mrow><mrow>
               &amp;= \frac{3}{8} + \frac{\cos(4\theta)}{8} + \frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Finally
  <me>
  \iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\int_0^{2\pi}\Big( \frac{3}{8} + \frac{\cos(4\theta)}{8}
               + \frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2}\Big)\,\dee{\theta}
  =\frac{3\pi}{4}
  </me>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m> \vF = x \sin y\,\vi - y \sin x\,\vj + (x - y)z^2\,\vk </m>. Au moyen du théorème de Stokes, calculer la valeur de
  <me>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  </me>
  le long du chemin formé par les segments de droites joignant successivement les points <m>P_0 = (0, 0, 0)</m>,   <m>P_1 = (\pi/2, 0, 0)</m>,
  <m>P_2 = (\pi/2, 0, 1)</m>,  <m>P_3 = (0, 0, 1)</m>,
  <m>P_4 = (0, \pi/2, 1)</m> et
  <m>P_5 = (0, \pi/2, 0)</m>, puis de retour à <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>.
  </p></statement>


  <answer><p>
  <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
  around a relatively complicated closed curve. That certainly suggests that
  we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. As we are to use
  Stokes' theorem, let's compute the curl
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  x \sin y &amp; - y \sin x &amp; (x - y)z^2
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-z^2\,\vi-z^2\,\vj -(y\cos x +x\cos y)\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Next we need to find a surface whose boundary is <m>\cC</m>.
  First, here is a sketch of <m>\cC</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="54%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE05D_8"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  We can choose the surface <m>\cS</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
  <ul>
  <li>
  the rectangle <m>S_x</m> in the <m>xz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(\frac{\pi}{2},0,0)</m>, <m>(\frac{\pi}{2},0,1)</m> and <m>(0,0,1)</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  the rectangle <m>S_y</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(0,0,1)</m>, <m>(0,\frac{\pi}{2},1)</m> and <m>(0,\frac{\pi}{2},0)</m>
  </li>
  </ul>
  The normal to <m>S_x</m> is <m>-\vj</m> and the normal to <m>S_y</m> is <m>-\vi</m>. Then Stokes'
  theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{S_x}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\vj)\,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{S_y}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\vi)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{z}\ z^2
    + \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{y}\int_0^1\dee{z}\ z^2
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{x}\ \frac{1}{3}
    + \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{y}\ \frac{1}{3}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{\pi}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Soit
  <me>
  \vF=\left( \frac{2z}{1+y}+\sin(x^2), \,
             \frac{3z}{1+x}+\sin(y^2), \,
             5(x+1)(y+2) \right)
  </me>
  et <m>\cC</m> la courbe orientée formée des segments de droites joignant successivement les points  <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(2,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,0,2)</m>, <m>(0,3,0)</m> et de retour à <m>(0,0,0)</m>.
  </p>

  <p><ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Faire une figure montrant <m>\cC</m> et l'orientation de chaque segment.
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer la valeur de <m>\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <answer>
  <p>(a)</p>
  <sidebyside width="58%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17D_4"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
    (b) <m>\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = 10</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p> (a) Here is a sketch.</p>

  <sidebyside width="58%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17D_4"/>
  </sidebyside>


  <p>
  (b) We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
  around a relatively complicated closed curve. That certainly suggests that
  we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. Let's try
  Stokes' theorem. First, we compute the curl
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
         \frac{2z}{1+y}+\sin(x^2) &amp; \frac{3z}{1+x}+\sin(y^2) &amp; 5(x+1)(y+2)
         \end{matrix} \right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \Big(5(x+1)-\frac{3}{1+x}\Big)\,\vi
    -\Big(5(y+2)-\frac{2}{1+y}\Big)\,\vj
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip1in  +\Big(-\frac{3z}{(1+x)^2}+\frac{2z}{(1+y)^2}\Big)\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Next we need to find a surface <m>\cS</m> whose boundary is <m>\cC</m>.
  We can choose the surface <m>\cS</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
  <ul>
  <li>
  the triangle <m>S_x</m> in the <m>xz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(2,0,0)</m>, and <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  the triangle <m>S_y</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
  <m>(0,0,2)</m>, and <m>(0,3,0)</m>
  </li>
  </ul>
  Note that
  <ul>
  <li>
  The normal to <m>S_x</m> specified by Stokes' theorem is <m>-\vj</m>. On <m>S_x</m>
  we have <m>y=0</m>, so that <m>\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vj</m> simplifies to
  <m>-\big(5(0+2)-\frac{2}{1+0}\big)=-8</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  The normal to <m>S_y</m> specified by Stokes' theorem is <m>-\vi</m>. On <m>S_y</m>
  we have <m>x=0</m>, so that <m>\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vi</m> simplifies to
  <m>\big(5(0+1)-\frac{3}{1+0}\big)=2</m>.
  </li>
  </ul>
  So Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{S_x}  \overbrace{\vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\vj)}^{8}\,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{S_y}  \overbrace{\vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\vi)}^{-2}\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=8\,\text{Area}(S_x)  -2\,\text{Area}(S_y)
    =8\frac{1}{2}(2)(2) -2\frac{1}{2}(3)(2)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=10
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
