  <!-- <exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title> -->
  <exercise>  
  <statement><p>
  Calculer  <m>\displaystyle\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m>, où
  <m>\vF=y\,\vi+2z\,\vj+3x\,\vk</m> et <m>\cS</m> est la surface  <m>z=\sqrt{1-x^2-y^2}</m>, <m>z\geqslant 0</m> orientée par un vecteur normal unitaire  <m>\vn</m> vérifiant <m>\vn\cdot\vk\geqslant 0</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
   The boundary, <m>\partial \cS</m>, of <m>\cS</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>
  oriented counter clockwise as usual. It may be parametrized by
  <m>\vr(\theta)=\cos\theta\,\vi+\sin\theta\vj</m>, <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m>. By Stokes' theorem
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;=\oint_{\partial S} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =\int_0^{2\pi}\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot\diff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta)
         \,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp; =\int_0^{2\pi}(\sin\theta,0,3\cos\theta)\cdot(-\sin\theta,\cos\theta,0)
          \,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
  =-\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\,\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\left[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
  <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2\theta</m>, see Example
  <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2000D</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cS</m> la surface
  <me>
  x^2 + y^2 + 2(z-1)^2 = 6, \quad z \geqslant 0
  </me>
  orientée par le vecteur normal unitaire qui pointe vers l'extérieur
  (par exemple, au point le plus haut de la surface, le vecteur normal est  <m>\vk</m>).
  </p>

  <p>Soit
  <me>
  \vG = \nabla\times\vF,
  \quad\text{où}\quad
  \vF = (xz - y^3\cos z)\,\vi + x^3 e^z\,\vj + xyze^{x^2+y^2+z^2}\,\vk.
  </me>
  Calculer <m>\displaystyle \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\dee{S}</m>.
  </p>

  </statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>24\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The given surface is an ellipsoid centred at <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,1)</m>.
  It caps a curve <m>\cC</m> in the plane <m>z=0</m>, given by <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>.
  This is a circle of radius <m>2</m> centred at the origin, oriented
  counterclockwise when viewed from the positive <m>z</m>-axis.
  </p>

  <p><em>Method I <mdash/> double Stokes':</em>
  Let <m>\cD</m> denote the plane disk <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 4</m>, <m>z=0</m>.
  Using Stokes' theorem twice gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \iint_\cS \nabla\times\vF\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  = \oint_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  = \iint_\cD \nabla\times\vF\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \iint_\cD \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Now in <m>\cD</m> we have <m>\vn=\vk</m> and <m>z=0</m>, so on this surface,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vG\cdot\vn
  = (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vk
  &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix} 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
  \frac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \frac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp; \frac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
  (xz - y^3\cos z) &amp; x^3 e^z &amp; xyze^{x^2+y^2+z^2} \end{matrix}\right]_{z=0}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \big[3x^2 e^z + 3y^2\cos z\big]_{z=0}
  = 3(x^2+y^2)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Hence, using polar coordinates,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \iint_\cD 3(x^2+y^2)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  = 3\int_{\theta=0}^{2\pi} \int_{r=0}^2 (r^2)\,r\,\dee{r}\,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 3(2\pi)(4)= 24\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p><em>Method II <mdash/> single Stokes':</em>
  By Stokes' theorem
  <me>
  \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  = \iint_\cS \nabla\times\vF\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  = \oint_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  </me>
  Parametrize the circle <m>\cC</m> using
  <me>
  \vr(\theta) = 2\cos\theta\,\vi + 2\sin\theta\,\vj,\qquad 0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi
  </me>
  to obtain
  <me>
  \dee{\vr} = \diff{\vr}{\theta}\,\dee{\theta}
  = (-2\sin\theta\,\vi + 2\cos\theta\,\vj)\,\dee{\theta}.
  </me>
  Then since <m>z=0</m> on <m>\cC</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \int_{0}^{2\pi}\!\!\big(
  \overbrace{-(2\sin\theta)^3\,\vi \!+\! (2\cos\theta)^3\,\vj}^
                                            {\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)}\big)
  \cdot \big(\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\vi \!+\! 2\cos\theta\,\vj}^{\vr'(\theta)}\big)
   \,\dee{\theta}

  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 16 \int_{0}^{2\pi}\big(\sin^4\theta + \cos^4\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}

  </mrow>
  </md>
  By the double angle trig identities
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \cos^2\theta=\frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\qquad
  \sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\qquad
  </mrow>
  </md>
  we have
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \sin^4\theta + \cos^4\theta
  &amp;=\frac{\big[1-\cos(2\theta)\big]^2}{4}
   + \frac{\big[1+\cos(2\theta)\big]^2}{4}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{2} + \frac{\cos^2(2\theta)}{2}
  =\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1+\cos(4\theta)}{4}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So
  <me>
  \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  =16\int_{0}^{2\pi} \left(\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{4}\cos(4\theta)\right)
                     \,\dee{\theta}
  = 16\times\frac{3}{4}\times (2\pi) = 24\pi
  </me>
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 1999A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
   Soit <m>\cC</m> un cercle de rayon <m>R</m> contenu dans le plan <m>x+y+z=3</m>. Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour calculer
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}.
  </me>
  où <m>\vF=z^2\vi+x^2\vj+y^2\vk</m> (utiliser n'importe quelle orientation du cercle).
  </p>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Soit <m>\cD</m> le disque dans le plan <m>x+y+z=3</m> dont la frontière est <m>\cC</m>.
      Supposons que, lorsque <m>(x,y,z)</m> parcourt <m>\cD</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> parcourt l'ellipse <m>D_{xy}</m>.
      On nous dit que l'aire de <m>\cD</m> est <m>\pi R^2</m>, mais on ne nous dit pas l'aire de <m>D'</m>. 
      Il est donc plus facile de traiter l'intégrale <m>\int{\cD}\dee{S}</m> que l'intégrale <m>\iint_{D'}\dee{x}\dee{y}</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>


  <answer><p>
  <m>2\sqrt{3}\pi R^2</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Note that
  <me>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left|\begin{matrix}\vi&amp;\vj&amp;\vk\\
    \frac{\partial }{\partial x}&amp;
          \frac{\partial }{\partial y}&amp;
          \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\\
  z^2&amp;x^2&amp;y^2\end{matrix}\right|
  =2y\,\vi+2z\,\vj+2x\,\vk
  </me>
  Let <m>\cD</m> be the disk in the plane <m>x+y+z=3</m> whose boundary is <m>\cC</m> and let
  <m>\vn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\vi+\vj+\vk)</m> be the upward unit normal to <m>\cD</m>.
  If the circle is oriented counterclockwise, when viewed from above,
  then, by Stokes' theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\int{\cD}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
  \int{\cD}\big(2y\,\vi+2z\,\vj+2x\,\vk\big)\cdot(\vi+\vj+\vk)\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\iint_D2\overbrace{\big(x+y+z\big)}^{=3\text{ on } D}\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=2\sqrt{3}\int{\cD}\dee{S}
  =2\sqrt{3}\pi R^2
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cS</m> la surface formée de la partie supérieure et des 4 faces latérales du cube de sommets <m>(\pm 1, \, \pm 1, \, \pm 1)</m>, orientée vers l'extérieur du cube. Si  <m>\vF(x,y,z)=(xyz,xy^2,x^2yz)</m>, trouver le flux de <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Let <m>S'</m> be the bottom surface of the cube, oriented with
  normal <m>\vk</m>. Then, by Stokes' theorem, since <m>\partial S=\partial S'</m>,
  <me>
  \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
  =\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\oint_{\partial S'}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\iint_{S'}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
  </me>
  Since
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    xyz &amp; xy^2 &amp; x^2yz \end{matrix}\right]
  =\big(\cdots\,,\,\cdots\,,\,y^2-xz\big)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and <m>\vn=\vk</m> on <m>S'</m> and <m>z=-1</m> on <m>S'</m>
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{S'}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
  &amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\
           \big(\cdots,\cdots,y^2-xz\big)\cdot\vk\Big|_{z=-1}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\  (y^2+x)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\  y^2
  =2\times 2\int_0^1\dee{y}\ y^2
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{4}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>
  </solution>

  <solution>
  <p>
  The boundary of <m>\cS</m> is the square <m>\cC</m>, with sides <m>C_1</m>, <m>\cdots</m>, <m>C_4</m>,
  in the sketch
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="45%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cubeS"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  By Stokes' theorem,
  <me>
  \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
  =\oint_{C}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  </me>
  Parametrize <m>C_1</m> by <m>x</m>. That is, <m>\vr(x)= x\vi - \vj -\vk</m>, <m>-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1</m>.
  Since <m>\vr'(x) = \vi</m>, and <m>y=z=-1</m> on <m>C_1</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{C_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\vr'(x)\ \dee{x}
  =\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\vi\ \dee{x}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_{-1}^1\overbrace{x(-1)(-1)}^{xyz}\ \dee{x}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=0\qquad\text{(since $x$ is odd)}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Parametrize <m>C_2</m> by <m>y</m>. That is, <m>\vr(y)= \vi + y\,\vj -\vk</m>, <m>-1\leqslant y\leqslant 1</m>.
  Since <m>\vr'(y) = \vj</m>, and <m>x=1</m> on <m>C_2</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(y)\big)\cdot\vj\ \dee{y}
  =\int_{-1}^1\overbrace{y^2}^{xy^2}\ \dee{y}
  =\left[\frac{y^3}{3}\right]_{-1}^1
  =\frac{2}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Parametrize <m>C_3</m> by <m>x</m>. That is, <m>\vr(x)= x\vi + \vj -\vk</m> with <m>x</m> running
  from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>. (If you're nervous about this, parametrize
  by <m>t=-x</m>. That is <m>\vr(t)= -t\,\vi + \vj -\vk</m>, <m>-1\leqslant t\leqslant 1</m>.)
  Since <m>\vr'(x) = \vi</m>, and <m>y=1</m>, <m>z=-1</m> on <m>C_3</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{C_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\int^{-1}_1\!\! \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\vi\ \dee{x}
  =\int^{-1}_1\overbrace{x\ (1)(-1)}^{xyz}\ \dee{x}
  =0\quad\text{(since $x$ is odd)}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Parametrize <m>C_4</m> by <m>y</m>. That is, <m>\vr(y)= -\vi + y\,\vj -\vk</m>, with
  <m>y</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>. Since <m>\vr'(y) = \vj</m>, and <m>x=-1</m> on <m>C_4</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{C_4}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\int^{-1}_1 \vF\big(\vr(y)\big)\cdot\vj\ \dee{y}
  =\int^{-1}_1\overbrace{(-1)y^2}^{xy^2}\ \dee{y}
  =-\left[\frac{y^3}{3}\right]^{-1}_1
  =\frac{2}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  All together
  <me>
  \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\, \dee{S}
  =\int_{C_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
   +\int_{C_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_{C_4}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\frac{4}{3}
  </me>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de la rampe spirale (c'est une surface hélicoïdale) donnée par
  <me>
  x=u\cos v,\ y=u\sin v,\ z=v, \qquad
  0\leqslant u\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant v\leqslant 2\pi.
  </me>
  Soit  <m>\cC</m> le bord de  <m>\cS</m> avec l'orientation donnée par le vecteur normal pointant vers le haut. Trouver
  <me>
  \int_{\cC} y\,\dee{x}-x\,\dee{y}+ xy\,\dee{z}.
  </me>
  </p></statement>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-2\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Let's try Stokes' Theorem. Call <m>\vF=y\,\vi-x\,\vj+xy\,\vk</m>. Then
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    y &amp; -x &amp; xy \end{matrix}\right]
  =x\,\vi-y\,\vj-2\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Now compute <m>\vn\,\dee{S}</m> in the <m>(u,v)</m>-parametrization.
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vr(u,v)&amp;=\big(u\cos v, u\sin v, v\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  \pdiff{\vr}{u}(u,v)&amp;=\big(\cos v, \sin v, 0\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  \pdiff{\vr}{v}(u,v)&amp;=\big(-u\sin v, u\cos v, 1\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  \pdiff{\vr}{u}\times\pdiff{\vr}{v}
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \cos v &amp; \sin v &amp; 0 \\
                    -u\sin v&amp; u\cos v&amp; 1 \end{matrix}\right]
  =\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vn\,\dee{S}&amp;=\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)\,\dee{u}\,\dee{v}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Since <m>u\geqslant 0</m>, we do indeed have the upward pointing normal.
  So, Stokes' theorem tells us
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\int_{\cC} y\,\dee{x}-x\,\dee{y}+ xy\,\dee{z}
  =\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^1 \dee{u} \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\  \big(u\cos v, -u\sin v, -2\big)
  \cdot\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^1 \dee{u} \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\ \big(2u\sin v\cos v-2u\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\left[\int_0^1 \dee{u} \ u\right]
      \left[\int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\ \big(\sin 2v-2\big)\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\half(-4\pi)=-2\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <exercisegroup><introduction><application/></introduction>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> l'intersection de  <m>x+2y-z=7</m> et <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m>. La courbe  <m>\cC</m> est orientée dans le sens contraire des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en haut. Soit
  <me>
  \vF=\big(e^{x^2}+yz\big)\,\vi
     +\big(\cos(y^2)-x^2\big)\,\vj
     +\big(\sin(z^2)+xy\big)\,\vk.
  </me>
  Calculer <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  Étant donnée la forme de  <m>\vF</m>, une évaluation directe semble ardue.
  </p>

  <p>Les évaluations des intégrales peuvent être simplifiées en utilisant le barycentre <m>(\bar x,\bar y)</m> d'une r <m>\cR</m> dans le plan <m>xy</m>.
  is
  <me>
  \bar x =\frac{\iint_R x\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}\qquad
  \bar y =\frac{\iint_R y\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}
  </me>
  </p>

  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>24\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Given the form of <m>\vF</m>, direct evaluation looks hard. So let's try
  Stokes' theorem, using as <m>\cS</m> the part of the plane <m>G(x,y,z)=x+2y-z=7</m>
  that is inside <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m>. Then
  <me>
  \vn\,\dee{S} = \pm \frac{\vnabla G}{\vnabla G\cdot\vk}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  = \pm\big(\vi+2\vj-\vk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </me>
  As <m>\cC</m> is oriented counterclockwise when viewed from high, Stokes'
  theorem specifies the upward pointing normal so that
  <m>\vn\,\dee{S} = -\big(\vi+2\vj-\vk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>From the observations that
  <me>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    e^{x^2}+yz &amp; \cos(y^2)-x^2 &amp; \sin(z^2)+xy
                    \end{matrix} \right]
  =x\,\vi-(z+2x)\,\vk
  </me>
  and that we can rewrite <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m> as <m>(x-1)^2+4y^2=16</m>,
  we have
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\leqslant 16}\,
       [x\vi-(z+2x)\vk]\Big|_{z=-7+x+2y}\cdot(-1,-2,1)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\leqslant 16} [-x-(-7+x+2y+2x)]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\leqslant 16} [7-4x-2y]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  To evaluate the integrals of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> we use that, for any region <m>\cR</m>
  in the <m>xy</m>--plane,
  <me>
  \bar x =\frac{\iint_R x\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}\qquad
  \bar y =\frac{\iint_R y\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}
  </me>
  Our ellipse is <m>\frac{(x-1)^2}{4^2}+\frac{y^2}{2^2}=1</m>
  and so has area <m>\pi ab = \pi\times4\times 2=8\pi</m> and centroid
  <m>(\bar x,\bar y) = (1,0)</m>. So, using
  <m>R=\Set{(x,y)}{\frac{(x-1)^2}{4^2}+\frac{y^2}{2^2}\leqslant 1}</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_R [7-4x-2y]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\text{Area}(R) \big\{7-4\bar x-2\bar y\}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=8\pi[7-4\times 1-2\times 0]=24\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2012D</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Calculer le rotationnel du champ
  <m>\vF  = \big(2 + x^2 + z, \, 0, \, 3 + x^2 z\big)</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Soit  <m>\cC</m> la courbe dans <m>\R^3</m> allant de <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> au point <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>, formée de trois segments de droites consécutifs : de <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> à <m>(0, 0, 3)</m>, de <m>(0, 0, 3)</m> à <m>(0, 1, 0)</m> et de  <m>(0, 1, 0)</m> à <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>. Calculer
  <me>
  \int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}.
  </me>
  où <m>\vF</m> est le champ de la partie (a).
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  La partie (a) est une indication pour la partie (b). Esquissez la courbe de la partie  (b).
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>\vnabla\times\vF=(1-2xz)\,\vj</m></p><p>
  (b) <m>\frac{20}{3}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  (a)
  The curl is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  2+x^2+z &amp;  0 &amp; 3+x^2z
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =(1-2xz)\,\vj
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p> (b) We are going to use Stokes' theorem. The specified curve <m>\cC</m>
  is not closed and so is not the boundary of a surface. So we extend
  <m>\cC</m> to a closed curve <m>\tilde C</m> by appending to <m>\cC</m> the line segment <m>L</m>
  from <m>(2,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,0,0)</m>. In the figure below, <m>\cC</m> is the red curve
  and <m>\tilde C</m> is <m>\cC</m> plus the blue line segment.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="44%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12D_4"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  The closed curve <m>\tilde C</m> is boundary of the surface <m>\cS</m> that is the
  union of
  <ul>
  <li> the triangle <m>T_1</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane
  with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,0,3)</m> and <m>(0,1,0)</m>
  and with normal vector <m>-\vi</m> and
  </li>
  <li> the triangle <m>T_2</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
  with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1,0)</m> and <m>(2,0,0)</m>
  and with normal vector <m>-\vk</m>.
  </li>
  </ul>
  So, by Stokes' theorem
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_L \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =  \int_{\partial S} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  = \iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in= \iint_{T_1} \vnabla\times \vF\cdot(-\vi)\,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{T_2} \vnabla\times \vF\cdot(-\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in= \iint_{T_1} (1-2xz)\,\vj\cdot(-\vi)\,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{T_2} (1-2xz)\,\vj\cdot(-\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=0
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Consequently the integral of interest
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=- \int_L \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =- \int_2^0 (2+x^2)\,\dee{x}
  \quad\text{since } \dee{y}=\dee{z}=z=0  \text{ on } L
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^2 (2+x^2)\,\dee{x}
  ={\left[2x+\frac{x^3}{3}\right]}_0^2
  =\frac{20}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2012D</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Soit  <m>\cS</m> la surface en forme de seau formée par la portion du  cylindre <m>y^2 + z^2 = 9</m> comprise entre  <m>x = 0</m> et <m>x = 5</m> ainsi que par le disque sur le plan <m>yz</m> de rayon  <m>3</m> centré à l'origine (le seau <m>\cS</m> a une partie inférieure, mais pas de couvercle). Orienter <m>\cS</m> de sorte que le vecteur normal pointe vers l'extérieur. Calculer le flux de  <m>\vnabla\times\vG</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>, lorsque  <m>\vG = (x, -z, y)</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer le flux de <m>\vF = (2 + z, \, xz^2, \, x \cos y) </m> à travers  <m>\cS</m>, où <m>\cS</m> est comme dans la partie (a).
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  Afin de vous pratiquer, évaluez le flux de  (a)  deux fois <mdash/> une par le calcul direct, et l'autre avec le théorème de Stokes.
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>-18\pi</m> </p><p>
  (b) <m>-18\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  (a) <em>by direct evaluation:</em>
  The curl of <m>\vG</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vG
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  x &amp; -z &amp; y
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =2\vi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The part of <m>\cS</m> in the first octant is sketched in the figure on the left below.
  <m>\cS</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> the cylindrical surface
  <me>
  S_1 = \Set{(x,y,z)}{y^2+z^2=9,\ 0\leqslant x\leqslant 5}
  </me>
  and the disc
  <me>
  S_2 = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x=0,\ y^2+z^2\leqslant 9}
  </me>
  The normal <m>\vn</m> to <m>\cS_1</m> always points radially outward from the cylinder
  and so always has <m>\vi</m> component zero. The normal of <m>\cS_2</m> is <m>-\vi</m>.
  So the flux is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times \vG \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \iint_{S_1} 2\vi \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
     + \iint_{S_2} 2\vi \cdot (-\vi)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -2 \iint_{S_2} \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -2 \big(\pi 3^2\big) = -18\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p>(a) <em>using Stokes' theorem:</em>
  Let's use Stokes' theorem. The boundary <m>\partial \cS</m> of <m>\cS</m> is the cirlce
  <m>y^2+z^2=9</m>, <m>x=5</m>, oriented clockwise when viewed from far down the <m>x</m>-axis.
  We'll parametrize it by <m>\vr(\theta)=\big(5, 3\cos\theta, -3\sin\theta\big)</m>.
  Then Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vG\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;=\oint_{\partial S}\vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \big(5\,,\,3\sin\theta,3\cos\theta\big)\cdot
         \big(0\,,\,-3\sin\theta\,,\,-3\cos\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \big(-9\sin^2\theta-9\cos^2\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-18\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="33%">
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12D_6a"/>
  <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12D_6b"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
   (b)
  This time we'll use the divergence theorem. The surface <m>\cS</m> is not closed.
  So we'll use the auxilary surface formed by <q>topping <m>\cS</m> off</q>
  with the cap <m>T=\Set{(5,y,z)}{y^2+z^2\leqslant 9}</m>. If we give <m>T</m> the normal vector <m>\vi</m>, this auxiliary surface, the union of <m>\cS</m> and <m>T</m>, is the boundary of
  <m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{y^2+z^2\leqslant 9,\ 0\leqslant x\leqslant 5}</m>. So the divergence theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS}  \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  +\iint_T \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \iint_{\partial V} \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\tripInt_V \vnabla\cdot \vF\ \dee{V}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=0
  </mrow>
  </md>
  since <m>\vnabla\cdot \vF = 0</m>. Thus the flux of interest is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS}  \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;=-\iint_T \vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =-\iint_T \vF\cdot\vi\,\dee{S}
  =-\iint_T (2+z)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-2\iint_T \,\dee{S}
     \qquad\text{since } \iint_T z\,\dee{S}=0, \text{ because $z$ is odd}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -18\pi
      \qquad\text{since $T$ has area $9\pi$}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit
  <me>
  \vF(x, y, z) = \Big( \frac{y}{x} +x^{1+x^2}, \, x^2-y^{1+y^2}, \,
                         \cos^5(\ln z)\Big).
  </me>
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Donner le domaine <m>\cD</m> de <m>\vF</m>.
  </li>
  <li><p>
  Encercler les énoncés qui sont vrais :
  <ol marker="(i)">
  <li> <m>\cD</m> est connexe.
  </li>
  <li> <m>\cD</m> est simplement connexe.
  </li>
  <li> <m>\cD</m> est disconnexe.
  </li>
  </ol></p>
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer  <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> le carré dont les sommets sont <m>(3 \pm 1, 3 \pm 1, 2)</m> orienté dans le sens des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vu d'en bas. Calculer   <me>
  \int_{\cC} \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}.
  </me>
  </li>
  <li>
  Le champ <m>\vF</m> est-il conservatif?
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Le domaine <m>\cD</m> est ouvert, et de plus il a la propriété que  deux points quelconques de <m>\cD</m> peuvent être reliés par une courbe qui se trouve complètement dans <m>\cD</m>.
    </p>
  
    <p>
      Par définition, <m>\cD</m> est simplement connexe si toute courbe fermée simple dans <m>\cD</m> peut être contractée en un point de manière continue dans <m>\cD</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x \gt 0,\ y \gt 0,\ z \gt 0}</m>
  </p>

  <p>(b) Le domaine <m>\cD</m> est connexe et simplement connexe.
  </p>

  <p>(c) <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\big(2x-\frac{1}{x}\big)\vk</m>
  </p>

  <p>(d) <m>2\ln 2-24</m>
  </p>

  <p>(e) Non. <m>\vF</m> n'est pas conservatif.
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  (a)
  Since
  <ul>
  <li>
  <m>\frac{y}{x}</m> is defined when <m>x\ne 0</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  <m>x^{1+x^2}=e^{(1+x^2)\ln x}</m> is defined when <m>\ln x</m> is defined,
  which is when <m>x \gt 0</m> (assuming that we are not allowed to use complex numbers)
  and
  </li>
  <li>
  <m>y^{1+y^2}=e^{(1+y^2)\ln y}</m> is defined when <m>\ln y</m> is defined,
  which is when <m>y \gt 0</m> and
  </li>
  <li>
  <m>\cos^5(\ln z)</m> is defined when <m>\ln z</m> is defined,
  which when <m>z \gt 0</m>
  </li>
  </ul>
  the domain of <m>\vF</m> is
  <me>
  D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x \gt 0,\ y \gt 0,\ z \gt 0}
  </me>
  </p>

  <p> (b) The domain <m>\cD</m> is both connected (any two points in <m>\cD</m>
  can be joined by a curve that lies completely in <m>\cD</m>) and
  simply connected (any simple closed curve in <m>\cD</m> can be shrunk to a
  point continuously in <m>\cD</m>).
  </p>

  <p> (c) The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  \frac{y}{x} +x^{1+x^2} &amp; x^2-y^{1+y^2} &amp; \cos^5(\ln z)
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =\big(2x-\frac{1}{x}\big)\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p> (d)
  The integrand for direct evaluation looks very complicated.
  On the other hand <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is quite simple. So let's
  try Stokes' thoerem.
  Denote
  <me>
  S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{2\leqslant x\leqslant 4,\ 2\leqslant y\leqslant 4,\ z=2}
  </me>
  The boundary of <m>\cS</m> is <m>\cC</m>. Because of the clockwise orientation
  of <m>\cC</m>, we assign the normal vector <m>-\vk</m> to <m>\cS</m>. See the sketch below
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="37%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE10D_5"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  Then, by Stokes'
  theorem,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  = \iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\vk)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -\iint_{\cS} \big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -\int_2^4\dee{x}\int_2^4\dee{y}\ \big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)
   =-\int_2^4\dee{x}\ 2\big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp; = - 2\Big[x^2-\ln x\Big]_2^4
  =-2\big[12-\ln 2\big]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=2\ln 2-24
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p> (e) Since <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is not <m>\vZero</m>, <m>\vF</m> cannot
  be conservative.
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Une physicienne étudie un champ de vecteurs <m>\vF(x, y, z)</m>. Ses expériences permettent de conclure que <m>\vF</m> est de la forme
  <me>
  \vF(x, y, z) = xz\,\vi + (axe^y z + byz)\,\vj + (y^2 - xe^y z^2 )\,\vk
  </me>
  pour certains nombres réels  <m>a</m> et <m>b</m>. De plus, il est connu que
  <m>\vF = \vnabla\times\vG</m> pour un certain champ différentiable  <m>\vG</m>.
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Trouver  <m>a</m> et <m>b</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer l'intégrale de surface
  <me>
  \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}.
  </me>
  où  <m>\cS</m> est la portion de l'ellipsoïde <m>x^2 + y^2 + \frac{1}{4} z^2 = 1</m> telle que <m>z \geqslant 0</m>, orientée de sorte que le vecteur normal ait une composante <m>z</m> positive.
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  
  <!-- <hint><p>
  Voir <xref ref="sec_vectorPotential"/>.
  </p></hint>
 -->
  <answer><p>
  (a) <m>a=2</m>, <m>b=-1</m></p><p>
  (b) <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  (a)
  By the vector identity <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla\times\vG\big)=0</m>
  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_degTwoIdentities"/>.a).
  So we must have
  <md>
  <mrow>
  0&amp;=\vnabla\cdot\vF
    =\frac{\partial }{\partial x}\big(xz\big)
     + \frac{\partial }{\partial y}\big(axe^y z + byz\big)
     + \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\big(y^2 - xe^y z^2 \big)
  </mrow><mrow>
   &amp;= z + \big(axe^y z+bz\big) + \big(-2xe^yz\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
   &amp;= (1+b)z + (a-2)x e^y z
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So we need <m>a=2</m> and <m>b=-1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>(b)
  Note that the boundary, <m>\partial \cS</m>, is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=0</m>,
  oriented counter-clockwise. Also note that, if we knew what <m>\vG</m> was,
  we would be able to use Stokes' theorem to give
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  &amp;= \iint_{\cS}(\vnabla\times\vG)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\oint_{\partial S} \vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So let's find a vector potential <m>\vG</m>.
  That is, let's try and find a vector field
  <m>\vG= G_1\,\vi + G_2\,\vj + G_3\,\vk</m> that obeys <m>\vnabla\times\vG = \vF</m>,
  or equivalently,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \frac{\partial G_3}{\partial y} -\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial z} &amp;= F_1
           =xz
  </mrow><mrow>
  -\frac{\partial G_3}{\partial x} +\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial z}&amp;=F_2
           =2xe^y z - yz
  </mrow><mrow>
  \frac{\partial G_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial y}&amp;=F_3
           =y^2 - xe^y z^2
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Let's also require that <m>G_3=0</m>.
  <!--  TODO. Note 26.07.2023 : Il faudra faire la section / paragraphe sur les potentiels vectoriels et l'inclure comme il faut.
  -->
  <!--
  (If this is mysterious to you,
  review §<xref ref="sec_vectorPotential"/>.)
  -->
  Then the equations above simplify to
   <md>
  <mrow>
   -\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial z} &amp;=xz
  </mrow><mrow>
    \frac{\partial G_1}{\partial z} &amp;=2xe^y z - yz
  </mrow><mrow>
  \frac{\partial G_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial y}&amp;=y^2 - xe^y z^2
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Now  the first equation contains only a single unknown, namely <m>G_2</m> and we
  can find all <m>G_2</m>'s that obey the first equation simply by integrating
  with respect to <m>z</m>:
  <me>
  G_2 = -\frac{xz^2}{2} + N(x,y)
  </me>
  Note that, because <m>\frac{\partial }{\partial z}</m> treats <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
  as constants, the constant of integration <m>N</m> is allowed to depend on <m>x</m>
  and <m>y</m>.
  </p>

  <p>Similarly, the second equation contains only a single unknown,
  <m>G_1</m>, and is easily solved by integrating with respect to <m>z</m>.
  The second equation is satisfied if and only if
  <me>
  G_1 = xe^y z^2 - \frac{1}{2}yz^2 + M(x,y)
  </me>
  for some function <m>M</m>.
  </p>

  <p>Finally, the third equation is also satisfied
  if and only if <m>M(x,y)</m> and <m>N(x,y)</m> obey
  <me>
  \frac{\partial }{\partial x}\Big(-\frac{xz^2}{2} + N(x,y)\Big)
  -\frac{\partial }{\partial y}\Big(xe^yz^2-\frac{yz^2}{2} + M(x,y)\Big)
       =y^2 - xe^y z^2
  </me>
  which simplifies to
  <me>
  \frac{\partial N}{\partial x}(x,y) -\frac{\partial M}{\partial y}(x,y) =y^2
  </me>
  This is one linear equation in two unknowns, <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>.
  Typically, we can easily solve one linear equation in one unknown.
  </p>

  <p>So we are free to eliminate one of the unknowns by setting, for example,
  <m>M=0</m>, and then choosing any <m>N</m> that obeys
  <me>
  \frac{\partial N}{\partial x}(x,y) = y^2
  </me>
  Integrating with respect to <m>x</m> gives, as one possible choice, <m>N(x,y) = xy^2</m>. So we have found a vector potential. Namely
  <me>
  \vG = \Big( xe^y z^2 - \frac{1}{2}yz^2\Big)\,\vi
         +\Big(xy^2  -\frac{xz^2}{2}\Big)\,\vj
  </me>
  We can now evaluate the flux. Parametrize <m>\partial \cS</m>
  by
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vr(\theta) &amp; = \cos\theta\,\vi +\sin\theta\,\vj
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vr'(\theta) &amp; = -\sin\theta\,\vi +\cos\theta\,\vj
  </mrow>
  </md>
  with <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m>.
  So
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
     &amp;=\oint_{\partial S} \vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}
     \Big(\overbrace{\cos\theta\sin^2\theta\,\vj}^{\vG(\vr(\theta))}\Big)
      \cdot\overbrace{\big(-\sin\theta\,\vi +\cos\theta\,\vj\big)}^{\vr'(\theta)}
        \  \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\
                           \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{4}\int_0^{2\pi}  \big\{ 1-\cos^2(2\theta)\big\}\
                           \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{4}\int_0^{2\pi}  \Big\{ 1-\frac{1+\cos(4\theta)}{2}\Big\}\
                           \dee{\theta}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp; = \frac{1}{4}\ \frac{1}{2}\ 2\pi
      \qquad\text{since } \int_0^{2\pi} \cos(4\theta)\ \dee{\theta}=0
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{\pi}{4}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2006D</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> la courbe dans le plan  <m>xy</m> allant du point <m>(0, 0)</m> à <m>(5, 5)</m> formée par les segments de droites reliant successivement les points <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m>, <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,2)</m>, <m>(2,3)</m>,   <m>(3,3)</m>, <m>(3,4)</m>, <m>(4,4)</m>, <m>(4,5)</m> et <m>(5,5)</m>. Calculer
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr},
  </mrow>
  </md>
  où
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vF = y\,\vi + (2x - 10)\,\vj.
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Étant donné qu'il y a dix segments de droite dans <m>\cC</m>, il n'est probablement pas très efficace d'utiliser une évaluation directe.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-15</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Considering that there are ten line segments in <m>\cC</m>,
  it is probably not very efficient to use direct evaluation.
  Two other possible methods come to mind. If <m>\vF</m> is conservative,
  we can use <m>\vF</m>'s potential. Even if <m>\vF</m> is not conservative,
  it may be possible to efficiently use Stokes' (or Green's) theorem.
  So let's compute
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  y &amp; 2x-10 &amp; 0
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  As <m>\vnabla\times\vF\ne\vZero</m>, the vector field <m>\vF</m> is not conservative.
  As <m>\vnabla\times\vF\ne\vZero</m> is very simple, it looks like Stokes'
  theorem could provide an efficient way to compute the integral.
  The left figure below contains a sketch of <m>\cC</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="48%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE06D_2"/>
   <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE06D_2b"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  The curve <m>\cC</m> is not closed, and so is not the boundary of a surface,
  so we cannot apply Stokes' theorem directly. But we can easily
  come up with a surface whose boundary contains <m>\cC</m>. Let <m>\cR</m> be the shaded
  region in the figure on the right above. The boundary <m>\partial R</m>
  of <m>\cR</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> <m>\cC</m> and the line segment <m>L</m>.
  The normal of <m>\cR</m> for <m>-\vk</m> (since <m>\partial R</m> is oriented clockwise).
  So Stokes' theorem gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_L \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;= \iint_R  \vnabla\times\vF \cdot(-\vk)\ \dee{S}
  = \iint_R  (\vk) \cdot(-\vk)\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= -\text{Area}(R)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  <m>\cR</m> is the union of <m>5</m> triangles, each of height <m>1</m> and base <m>1</m>.
  So
  <me>
  \text{Area}(R) = 5\times \frac{1}{2}\times 1\times 1
  =\frac{5}{2}
  </me>
  If we denote by <m>-L</m> the line segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(5,5)</m>,
  we can parametrize <m>-L</m> by <m>\vr(t) = t(5,5)</m>, <m>0\leqslant t\leqslant 1</m> and
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{-L} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\int_0^1 \overbrace{\big(5t\,\vi + (10t-10)\,\vj\big)}^{\vF(\vr(t))}
                \cdot\overbrace{(5\,\vi+5\,\vj)}^{\vr'(t)}\ \dee{t}
  =\int_0^1 5\big(15t-10\big) \dee{t}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=25\left(\frac{3}{2}-2\right)
  =-\frac{25}{2}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  All together
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \int_{\cC} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;= -\text{Area}(R) - \int_L \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
  = -\text{Area}(R) + \int_{-L} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
  =-\frac{5}{2}-\frac{25}{2}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=-15
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\vF = \big(\sin x^2, \, xz, \, z^2\big)</m>. Calculer <m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> le long de la courbe <m>\cC</m> qui est l'intersection du cylindre  <m>x^2+y^2=4</m> avec la surface <m>z=x^2</m>, parcourue dans le sens contraire des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue d'en haut.
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  L'évaluation directe semble ardue...
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>12\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  If we parametrize the curve as
  <me>
  x = 2\cos\theta\qquad
  y = 2\sin\theta\qquad
  z= x^2 = 4\cos^2\theta\qquad
  0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi
  </me>
  then the term <m>\sin x(\theta)^2\ x'(\theta)</m> in the integral will be
  <m>\sin\big(4\cos^2\theta\big)\ (-2\sin\theta)</m>. That looks hard to integrate.
  So let's try Stokes' theorem.
  The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp;\vj &amp;\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  \sin x^2 &amp; xz &amp; z^2
  \end{matrix}
  \right]
  =-x\,\vi +z\,\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The curve <m>\cC</m> is the boundary of the surface
  <me>
  S = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 4,\ z=x^2}
  </me>
  with upward pointing normal.
  For the surface <m>z=f(x,y) = x^2</m>,
  (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>) gives
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\, \dee{S} &amp; = \pm\big[-f_x(x,y)\,\vi - f_y(x,y)\,\vj + \vk\big]\
            \dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
               &amp; = \pm \big[-2x\,\vi+\vk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Since we want the upward pointing normal
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vn\, \dee{S} &amp; = \big[-2x\,\vi+\vk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  So by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>)
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 4} \big(-x\,\vi + \overbrace{x^2}^{z}\vk\big)\cdot
  \big[-2x\,\vi+\vk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=3\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 4} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Switching to polar coordinates
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  &amp;=3\int_0^2\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^2\cos^2\theta
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=3\left[\int_0^2 r^3\,\dee{r}\right]
             \left[\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 3\ \frac{2^4}{4}
         \left[\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}\ \dee{\theta}\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= 12\pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
  <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t\ \dee{t}</m> see Example
  <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Expliquer comment la loi de Faraday, sous sa forme différentielle
  <me>
  \vnabla\times\vE = -\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t},
  </me>
  est déduite de la forme intégrale
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}\vE\cdot\dee{\vr} =
    -\frac{1}{c}\ \diff{ }{t}\iint_{\cS}\vH\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}.
  </me>
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  Écrivez <m>\oint_{\cC}\vE\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> comme une intégrale de surface.
  </p></hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      Réécrire <m>\oint_{\cC}\vE\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> comme une intégrale de surface. Puis utiliser le fait que si l'intégrale d'une fonction continue est nulle sur toute région, alors la fonction elle-même est nulle. 
  </p>
</answer>

<solution>
  <p>
    Par le théorème de Stokes,
    <me>
    \oint_{\cC}\vE\cdot \dee{\vr}=\iint_{\cS}(\vnabla\times\vE)\cdot \vn\,\dee{S}
    </me>
    donc la loi de Faraday devient
    <me>
      \iint_{\cS}\Big(\vnabla\times\vE +\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}=0
    </me>
    Ceci est vrai pour toutes les surfaces <m>\cS</m>. Ainsi, l'intégrande, en supposant qu'il est continu, doit être nul.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pour voir cela, soit <m>\vG=\Big(\vnabla\times\vE+\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)</m>. Supposons que <m>\vG(\vx_0)\ne 0</m>. Choisissez un vecteur unitaire <m>\vn</m> dans la direction de <m>\vG(\vx_0)</m>. Soit <m>\cS</m> un très petit disque plat centré sur <m>\vx_0</m> avec une normale <m>\vn</m> (le vecteur que nous avons choisi). Alors <m>\vG(\vx_0)\cdot\vn \gt 0</m> et, par continuité, <m>\vG(\vx)\cdot\vn \gt 0</m> pour tout <m>\vx</m> sur <m>\cS</m>, si nous avons choisi <m>\cS</m> assez petit. Alors <m>\iint_{\cS}\Big(\vnabla\times\vE + \frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)\cdot \vn\,\dee{S} \gt 0</m>, ce qui est une contradiction. Donc <m>\vG=\vZero</m> partout et nous concluons que
    <me>
    \vnabla\times\vE+\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}=0
    </me>
  </p>
</solution>

  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit <m>\cC</m> la courbe donnée par
  <me>
  x=\cos t,\
  y=\sqrt{2}\sin t,\
  z=\cos t,\
  0\leqslant t\leqslant 2\pi
  </me>
  et soit
  <me>
  \vF=z\,\vi+x\,\vj+y^3z^3\,\vk.
  </me>
  Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour calculer
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}.
  </me>
  </p></statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Qu'est-ce que <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2+z(t)^2=2</m>? Comment est-ce que <m>x(t)</m>   est liée à  <m>z(t)</m>?
  </p>
</hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>\sqrt{2}\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The curl of the specified vector field is
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \nabla\times\vF
  &amp;=\nabla\times\big(z\,\vi+x\,\vj+y^3z^3\,\vk\big)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}
  \vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
  </mrow><mrow>
  z &amp; x &amp; y^3z^3
  \end{matrix}\right]
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=3y^2z^3\,\vi+\vj+\vk
  </mrow>
  </md>
  For every <m>t</m>, we have <m>x(t)=z(t)</m> and <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2+z(t)^2=2</m>.
  So the specified curve is the intersection of the plane <m>x=z</m> and the sphere
  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m>. This curve is the boundary of the circular disk
  <me>
  D = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x=z,\ x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 2}
  </me>
  The curve is oriented so that
  <m>\big(x(t),y(t)\big)=\big(\cos t,\sqrt{2}\sin t\big)</m>
  runs in the standard (counterclockwise) direction. So the unit normal
  to <m>\cD</m> used in Stokes' theorem has positive <m>\vk</m> component. Since the
  plane <m>x-z=0</m> has unit normal <m>\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,0,-1)</m>, the unit
  normal used in Stokes' theorem is <m>\vn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(-1,0,1)</m>. By Stokes'
  theorem
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_D\nabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\ \dee{S}
  =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\iint_D(3y^2z^3,1,1)\cdot(-1,0,1)\ \dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\iint_D(1-3y^2z^3)\ \dee{S}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  The disk <m>\cD</m> is invariant under the reflection <m>(x,y,z)\rightarrow(-x,y,-z)</m>.
  Since <m>y^2z^3</m> is odd under this reflection, <m>\int{\cD}y^2z^3\ \dee{s}=0</m>
  and
  <me>
  \oint \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\int{\cD}\ \dee{S}
  =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{\rm Area}(D)
  </me>
  Because the centre of the ball <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 2</m> (namely <m>(0,0,0)</m>)
  is contained in the plane <m>x=z</m>, the radius of the disk <m>\cD</m> is the same
  as the radius of the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m>. So <m>\cD</m> has radius <m>\sqrt{2}</m> and
  <me>
  \oint \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{\rm Area}(D)
  =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\pi{\big(\,\sqrt{2}\,\big)}^2
  =\sqrt{2}\pi
  </me>
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2002A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Utiliser le théorème de Stokes pour calculer
  <me>
  \oint_{\cC}z\,\dee{x}+x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{z}
  </me>
  lorsque <m>\cC</m> est la courbe fermée donnée par l'intersection du plan <m>x+y+z=1</m> avec la sphère <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>. La courbe  <m>\cC</m> est orientée dans le sens des aiguilles d'une montre lorsque vue de l'origine.
  </p></statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      L'intersection du plan  <m>x+y+z=1</m> avec la sphère <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> est un cercle. Servez-vous de la symétrie pour touver son centre.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>\frac{2\pi}{3\sqrt{3}}</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  The curl of the vector field <m>\vF=z\,\vi+x\,\vj-y\,\vk</m> is
  <me>
  \vnabla\times\vF=-\vi+\vj+\vk
  </me>
  The unit normal to the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m>, with positive <m>\vk</m> component as
  required by Stokes' theorem in this case, is <m>\vn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(1,1,1)</m>.
  If we denote by <m>\cD</m> the circular disk <m>x+y+z=1</m>, <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 1</m>, then
  Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) says
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \oint_{\cC}z\,\dee{x}+x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{z}=\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  &amp;=\iint_D\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\iint_D(-1,1,1)\cdot\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(1,1,1)\,\dee{S}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}{\rm Area}(D)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  A reasonable guess for the centre of the disk is <m>\frac{1}{3}(1,1,1)</m>.
  (This guess is just based on symmetry.) To check
  this we just need to observe that it is indeed on the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m>
  and that the distance from  <m>\frac{1}{3}(1,1,1)</m> to any point <m>(x,y,z)</m>
  obeying <m>x+y+z=1</m> and <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>, namely
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\sqrt{{\Big(x-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2+{\Big(y-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2
  +{\Big(z-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip1in=\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2-\frac{2}{3}(x+y+z)+\frac{3}{9}}
  =\sqrt{1-\frac{2}{3}+\frac{1}{3}}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip1in=\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  is the same. This also tells us that <m>\cD</m> has radius
  <m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m> and hence area <m>\frac{2}{3}\pi</m>. So the specified
  line integral is <m>\frac{2\pi}{3\sqrt{3}}</m>.
  </p></solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <!-- <title><fromexam>M317 2018A</fromexam></title> -->
  <statement><p>
  Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion du demi-cône   <me>
  z=\sqrt{x^2+y^2},\quad  y\geqslant 0,
  </me>
  qui se trouve en dessous du plan <m>z=1</m>.
  <ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
  Donner un paramétrage de <m>\cS</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Calculer le  flux du champ   <me>
  \vv=x\,\vi + y\, \vj -2 z\,\vk
  </me>
  vers le bas à travers  <m>\cS</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
  Un champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF</m> a pour rotationnel <m>\vnabla\times \vF= x\, \vi + y\, \vj -2 z\,\vk</m>. Sur le plan <m>xz</m>, le champ est constant, avec  <m>\vF(x,0,z)=\vj</m>. Avec cette information, calculer
  <me>
  \int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr},
  </me>
  où  <m>\cC</m> est le demi-cercle
  <me>
  x^2+y^2=1,\ z=1,\ y\geqslant 0
  </me>
  orienté de <m>(-1,0,1)</m> à <m>(1,0,1)</m>.
  </li>
  </ol>
  </p></statement>

  <hint><p>
  Esquissez <m>\cS</m>.
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  (a) Une paramétrisation possible est
  <m>\vr(r, \theta) = r\cos \theta\, \vi +r\sin \theta\, \vj + r\,\vk</m>
  avec <m>0\leqslant r\leqslant 1</m>, <m>0\leqslant \theta \leqslant \pi</m>.
  </p>

  <p>(b) <m>\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>  (a)
  We parametrize <m>\cS</m> in cylindrical coordinates:
  <me>
  \vr(r, \theta) = r\cos \theta\, \vi +r\sin \theta\, \vj + r\,\vk
               \qquad \text{with } 0\leqslant r\leqslant 1, 0\leqslant \theta \leqslant \pi
  </me>
  </p>

  <p>(b)
  We compute
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial r}
      &amp;= \cos \theta \,\vi +\sin \theta \,\vj +\,\vk
  </mrow><mrow>
  \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial \theta}
      &amp;= -r \sin \theta \,\vi + r\cos \theta \,\vj
  </mrow><mrow>
  \vn\, \dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial r}\times
                       \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial \theta}
                     \ \dee{r}  \dee{\theta}
           = \pm \big(-r\cos \theta \,\vi - r \sin \theta \,\vj + r \,\vk\big)\,
                     \dee{r} \dee{\theta}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  To calculate the downward flux, we use the minus sign. We find
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \iint_{\cS} \vv \cdot \vn\, \dee{S}
  &amp; = \int_0^\pi \dee{\theta} \int_0^1 \dee{r}\  (r \cos \theta, r\sin \theta, -2r)\cdot
                     (r\cos \theta, r\sin \theta, -r)
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \int_0^\pi \dee{\theta} \int_0^1 \dee{r}\  3 r^2
    = \pi r^3\Big|_{r=0}^1 = \pi
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>

  <p>(c) <em>Solution 1</em>:
  Let <m>\cP</m> be the path along line segments from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(0,0,0)</m>
  and from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0,1)</m>. Here is a sketch. <m>\cP</m> is
  in blue.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="43%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/halfCone"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  Then
  <me>
  \int_\cC \vF \cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_\cP \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
  = \iint_{\cS} \vnabla \times \vF \cdot \vn\, \dee{S}
  </me>
  by Stokes' Theorem. Along <m>\cP</m>, the vector field <m>\vF</m> is orthogonal
  to the curve so that <m>\int_\cP \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>. Note that
  <m>\nabla\times \vF</m> is the vector field <m>\vv</m> from part (b).
  Thus
  <me>
  \int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr} = \iint_{\cS} \vv \cdot \vn\, \dee{S} = \pi
  </me>
  </p>

  <p>(c) <em>Solution 2:</em>
  Let <m>\cL</m> be the  line segment from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(-1,0,1)</m> and
  let
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \cR=\set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\le1, y\geqslant 0, z=1}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  Here is a sketch. <m>\cL</m> is in blue and <m>\cR</m> is shaded.
  </p>

  <sidebyside width="47%">
    <image source="images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/halfConeB"/>
  </sidebyside>

  <p>
  Then
  <me>
  \int_\cC \vF \cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_\cL \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
  = \iint_{\cR} \vnabla \times \vF \cdot (-\vk)\, \dee{S}
  </me>
  by Stokes' Theorem. Along <m>\cL</m>, the vector field <m>\vF=\vj</m> is orthogonal
  to the curve (which has direction <m>-\vi</m> so that <m>\int_\cL \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>. Note that
  <m>\nabla\times \vF</m> is the vector field <m>\vv</m> from part (b).
  Thus
  <me>
  \int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr} = -\iint_\cR \vv \cdot \vk\, \dee{S}
  = \iint_\cR 2z \, \dee{S}
  = 2\iint_\cR \, \dee{S}
  =2\,\text{Area}(\cR)
  = \pi
  </me>
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement><p>
  Soit  <m>\iint_{\cS}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS</m>, où <m>\cS</m> est la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> vérifiant <m>x+y+z\geqslant 1</m>, <m>\vn</m> est le vecteur normal qui pointe vers le haut et
   <m>\vF=(y-z)\vi+(z-x)\vj+(x-y)\vk</m>. Trouver une autre surface  <m>\cS'</m> avec la propriété que <m>\iint_{\cS}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\iint_{\cS'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m> et évaluer
  <m>\iint_{\cS'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}</m>.
  </p></statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Il est possible de se passer de l'évaluation de toute intégrale, il faut identifier  <m>\cS'</m> comme une figure simple.
  </p></hint>

  <answer><p>
  <m>-\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\pi</m>
  </p></answer>

  <solution><p>
  Let <m>S'</m> be the portion of <m>x+y+z=1</m> that is inside the sphere
  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>. Then <m>\partial S=\partial S'</m>, so, by  Stokes' theorem,
  (with <m>\vn</m> always the upward pointing normal)
  <me>
  \iint_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\oint_{\partial S'}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\iint_{S}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  </me>
  As
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\vi &amp; \vj &amp; \vk \\
                    \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                    \pdiff{}{z} \\
                    y-z &amp; z-x &amp; x-y \end{matrix}\right]
  =-2(\vi+\vj+\vk)
  </mrow>
  </md>
  and, on <m>S'</m>,
  <m>\vn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\vi+\vj+\vk)</m>
  <me>
  \iint_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =\iint_{S'}\big(-2\sqrt{3}\big)\,\dee{S}
  =-2\sqrt{3}\times{\rm Area}(S')
  </me>
  <m>S'</m> is the intersection of a plane with a sphere and so is a circular disk. It's center <m>(x_c,y_c,z_c)</m> has to obey
  <m>x_c+y_c+z_c=1</m>. By symmetry, <m>x_c=y_c=z_c</m>, so <m>x_c=y_c=z_c=\frac{1}{3}</m>.
  Any point, <m>(x,y,z)</m>, which satisfies both <m>x+y+z=1</m> and <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>,
  obeys
  <md>
  <mrow>
  &amp;\left(x-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2+\left(y-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2
  +\left(z-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip1in=x^2+y^2+z^2-\frac{2}{3}(x+y+z)+3\frac{1}{9}
  </mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip1in=1-\frac{2}{3} +\frac{1}{3}=\frac{2}{3}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  That is, any point on the boundary of <m>S'</m> is a distance <m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m>
  from <m>\big(\frac{1}{3}\,,\,\frac{1}{3}\,,\,\frac{1}{3}\big)</m>.
  So the radius of <m>S'</m> is <m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m>,
  the area of <m>S'</m> is <m>\frac{2}{3}\pi</m> and
  <me>
  \iint_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,\dee{S}
  =-2\sqrt{3}\times{\rm Area}(S')
  =-\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\pi
  </me>
  </p>

  </solution>
  </exercise></exercisegroup>

